{"title_page": "William Edmondson", "text_new": "'''William Edmondson''' (c.1874\u20131951) was the first [[African-American]] [[folk art]] [[sculptor]] to be given a [[one-person show]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]] (1937).{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Edmondson\n| image              = File:William Edmonson.jpg\n| caption            = William Edmondson at work\n| birth_date         = December, 1874\n| birth_place        = Davidson County, Nashville, Tennessee\n| death_date         = February 7th, 1951\n| death_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| othername          = \n| birthname          = William Edmondson\n| occupation         = Sculptor\n}}\n==Biography==\nWilliam Edmondson was born sometime in December 1874 on the Compton Plantation in [[Davidson County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Thompson|first=Robert Farris|title=The Art of William Edmondson|last2=Lovett|first2=Bobby L.|last3=Freeman|first3=Rusty|last4=McWillie|first4=Judith|date=January 1, 1999|publisher=Cheekwood Museum of Art|year=1999|isbn=1578061814|location=Cheekwood Museum of Art|pages=3-14, 15-32, 33-44, 45-60|oclc=41932532}}</ref> He did not know the date of his birth because of a fire that destroyed the family Bible.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last1=Edmondson |first1=William |last2=Thompson |first2=Robert Farris |last3=Freeman |first3=Rusty |title=The Art of William Edmondson |date=1999 |publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi |isbn=9781578061815 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCOLisQ4eCkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=10 things to know about William Edmondson |url=https://www.christies.com/features/William-Edmondson-10-things-to-know-8027-1.aspx |website=Christie's |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Edmondson was one of six children born to Orange and Jane Edmondson who had been and previously enslaved before they worked as sharecroppers. Due to privilege regarding race and color, mulattoes on the plantation were given more respectable jobs where as the Edmonson's  mainly worked in the corn fields and handled livestock. The Edmondson family worked on the plantation and earned a mere 12 dollars a month. During these times in the corn fields he would see \"angels in the clouds\" and believe it was God talking to him. <ref name=\":1\" />  Edmondson had little or no formal education. \n\nWhen his father died in late 1889,16 year-old Edmondson refused to continue to tirelessly work on the plantation and left to Nashville for work.<ref name=\":1\" /> He got a good job working at the expansive new [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railroad]] shops. After an injury sustained at the Railway shops in 1907, Edmondson took a job as a custodian at the Nashville Women's Hospital, where he worked until the hospital closed in 1931<ref name=\":2\" />. During this time Edmondson family officially resided in Nashville as his mother, Jane, was the last to leave the Compton Plantation. By age 39, his wages at Women's Hospital allowed him to buy a modest home and spacious lot in Edgehill, a segregated neighborhood in Nashville's Vanderbilt-Belmont area<ref name=\":1\" />.  Edmondson never married and he shared the home with his mother and sister, as well as, occasionally, other siblings, nieces, and nephews. With Jane's passing in 1922, Edmonson's sister, Sarah, soon became the woman of the house. It was said she would often hold family barbecues that consisted of laughter and storytelling.<ref name=\":1\" />  When the hospital closed in 1931, Edmondson picked up work at various part-time jobs and in his leisure, he could be found in his backyard sculpting and selling his vegetables.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n\nIn 1948 Edmondson stopped sculpting. On February 7th, 1951 at age seventy-six, he passed quietly in his home in Nashville, Tennessee, where illness had confined him to bed for several months. As he was the last of his siblings to pass, his five nieces and seven nephews carried out his funeral service which was held the next day<ref name=\":1\" />. William Edmondson was buried in Mount Ararat Cemetery, now [[Greenwood Cemetery (Nashville, Tennessee)]], Nashville's oldest black cemetery. Today there is no sign of Edmondson's grave marker because at the time cheap wooden caskets were used to bury African Americans. As the wood decayed it would cause the grave markers to sink into the earth.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mt. Ararat burial records of the period were lost in a fire, so his exact grave site is unknown.  \n\n== Art Career ==\n[[File:Crucifix_ca._1932-1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|369x369px|\"Crucifixion\" ca. 1932-1937, carved limestone, gift from Elizabeth Gibbons-Hanson]]\nEdmondson entered the world of sculpture at the advanced age of about 60 years old in 1934. He reported that he received a vision from God, who told him to start sculpting: \"I was out in the driveway with some old sculptures of stone when I heard a voice telling me to pick up my tools and start to work on a tombstone. I looked up in the sky and right there in the noon daylight, he hung a tombstone out for me to make. I knowed it was God telling me what to do.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jack|first=Lindsey|title=Miracles : the sculptures of William Edmondson.|last2=Pa.)|first2=Janet Fleisher Gallery (Philadelphia|isbn=0962150630|oclc=32664611}}</ref> He carved tombstones primarily from chunks of discarded limestone from demolished buildings, which were delivered to him by wrecking companies' trucks. A signature Edmondson tombstone reflects strong large lettering carved in the stone<ref name=\":1\" />. He began his career by working on these tombstones, which he sold or gave to friends and family in the community. Soon he began carving lawn ornaments, birdbaths, and decorative sculptures. In his yard hung a sign \"Tomb-Stones. For Sale. Garden. Ornaments. Stone Work W M Edmondson\". <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spires|first=Elizabeth|title=I Hear God Talking to Me|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2009|isbn=9780374335281|location=New York|pages=50-52}}</ref> \n\nEdmondson's work was influenced by his [[Christianity|Christian]] faith and his membership in a nearby [[Primitive Baptist]] congregation. His sculptures are straightforward and emphatic forms ranging from one to three feet in height, many sharing his unique religious symbolism. He carved figures of biblical characters, angels, doves, turtles, eagles, rabbits, horses and other real and fanciful creatures. His sculpture ''Noah's Ark'' stood tall in the middle of his backyard. It consists for four differently carved tiers of limestone and is the only architectural work that existed in his collection.<ref name=\":1\" />, He carved local community icons such as preachers, lawyers and school teachers, celebrities of the day who were important to the [[African American]] community, such as prizefighter [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio/william-edmondson/|title=WILLIAM EDMONDSON|work=Ricco Maresca Gallery|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> He also sculpted a number of popular figures such as First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Edmondson also created and a small number of nude figures.<ref>''[http://www.rawvision.com/books/outsider-art-sourcebook Outsider Art Sourcebook]'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009, p.70</ref> Most of Edmonson's carved figures consisted of faces carved on a spherical base, with a small mouth resting directly under a vertical nose, following to connect to the curve of the brow. Sometimes he would decide not to carve the eyebrows and would opt to make the nose broader. It is believed he did this to achieve racial inclusion within his collection of artwork<ref name=\":1\" />. Even with versatility of his artwork, the common characteristic of an Edmondson sculpture was the overbuilt-ness of the figures carved within or from the limestone. Intentional texturing ranging between smooth, chiseled, polished or rough was present throughout the make of each sculpture.<ref name=\":1\" />  The facial technique, overbuiltness, and range in texturing can be observed in Edmonson's most well known masterpiece ''Bess and Joe'' and further with ''Mary and Martha'' <ref name=\":1\" />.  \n\nEdmondson had a large audience in Edgehill and as many of his figures were on display not only in his yard, but in that of neighbors homes and gardens.  Around 1935, about a few years into this sculpting career, [[Peabody College]] art enthusiast, Sidney Hirsch, wandered though Edgehill and caught eye of Edmondson's vast sculpture collection.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Amico|first=Michael|url=https://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/distributed/E/bo27331575.html|title=Experience|last2=Mackintosh|first2=Lucy|last3=Jane Marshall|first3=Jennifer|last4=Peters Corbett|first4=David|last5=Situ|first5=Xiao|last6=Slifkin|first6=Robert|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2017|isbn=9780932171634|editor-last=Nemerov|editor-first=Alexander|location=Chicago|pages=102-133}}</ref> This is widely documented as Edmondson's \"discovery\" by [[Sidney Mttron Hirsch]]. Hirsch himself was a collector of African, Middle Eastern, and East Asian art and began to become one of Edmondson's greatest supporters .<ref name=\":3\" />  With this exposure, friends of Hirsch's and other fellow members of Nashville's elite bought Edmondson's sculptures for their homes, gardens, and offices, many of which were later displayed in exhibits at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Jennifer Jane|date=2017|title=Nashville, New York, Paris, and Nashville: William Edmondson, Mobilized and Unmoved|url=|journal=American Art|volume=31|pages=69-76|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Of Hirsch's friends, Alfred and Elizabeth Starr, Alfred, a managing partner of a chain of movie theaters catering to the black community, and his wife Elizabeth, a painter, also became enthusiastic patrons and supporters of Edmondson's work.  They introduced Edmondson to several artist friends, including Starr's boyhood friend Meyer (Mike) Wolfe and his wife [[Louise Dahl-Wolfe]]. Dahl-Wolfe was a photographer who had recently begun work for ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' fashion magazine in [[New York City|New York]]. She made over a hundred of photographs of Edmondson's at work in his backyard shop, which she presented to the editor of Harper's Bazaar''.'' She attempted to publish his work but newspaper chain mogul [[William Randolph Hearst]], had a prejudice against showing Negro art as he seen them as nothing other than servants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/william-edmondson-down-home-artist-forging-beauty-stone|title=William Edmondson, a down home artist forging beauty from stone|work=aaregistry.org|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=\":4\" /> She then brought Edmondson's work to the attention of fellow Tennessean Thomas Mabry and his boss [[Alfred Barr]], the director of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA)<ref name=\":1\" />.  \n\nEdmondson's career lasted for about fifteen years. His work never commanded large sums during his lifetime. In 1939 and again in 1941, he worked under the [[Works Progress Administration]], a government sponsored relief program that included artists. In the late 1940s, his health began to fail and his artistic production slowed. Edmondson professed to be uninterested in fame, and he appears to have struggled financially for the final years of his life. He is believed to have created about 300 works during his working lifetime.  \n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Bird_ca._1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|291x291px|Bird ca. 1937, carved limestone, gift from Margaret Z. Robson]]\nEdmondson was given a one-man show, the first by an African American artist, at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] from October 20th to December 1st 1937<ref name=\":1\" />. In 1938, through MoMA's influence, William Edmondson's sculpture was included in the \"Three Centuries of Art in the United States\" in [[Paris, France|Paris]]. Interest in his work on the national and international stage was short-lived, and he was viewed primarily as a novelty, or exemplar of the \"primitive\" race-memory of an untutored, naive old Negro stone carver. Locally, Alfred Starr continued to promote Edmondson's work to his artistic friends and acquaintances, who bought work directly from Edmondson's \"sculpture yard\" or through the local Lyzon Gallery. Starr introduced the famed modernist photographer [[Edward Weston]] to Edmondson in 1941, and Weston made several striking photographs of Edmondson at work in his shop and yard. Also in 1941, he received the only other solo show accorded during his lifetime, at the Nashville Art Gallery.\n\nAfter very sporadic exhibition through the 1950s and 1960s (mostly as part of \"folk art\" exhibits), collector [[Edmund Fuller]] wrote a biography of Edmondson which was published in 1973. His sculpture was included in the influential \"[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]\" exhibition curated by [[Fisk University]] Art Department chairman [[David C. Driskell]] in 1976.  In 1981 the new [[Tennessee State Museum]] opened with a permanent solo exhibition with six of Edmondson's sculptures featuring loaned sculptures from Elizabeth Starr's personal collection<ref name=\":1\" />, and the essays in the accompanying catalog sought to elevate appreciation of Edmondson's work as fine art. Through the 1980s and 1990s Edmondson's sculptures were exhibited extensively, though often in the limiting context of the labels \"outsider\", \"folk art\", \"self-taught\", and \"naive\". In 1999, Nashville's [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art|Cheekwood Museum of Art]] mounted a major traveling retrospective exhibition and catalog that included in-depth biographical and critical essays on his life and work This exhibit also sculptures from Elizabeth Starrs personal collection of which she donated to the museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2006 exhibition, \"William Edmondson, Bill Traylor, and the Modernist Impulse,\" paired Edmondson with another well-known self-taught artist and argued for Edmondson's acceptance as an artist without limiting labels. This exhibit displeayed twenty-one of Edmondon's sculptures which is the largest collection of Edmondson's art in the country<ref name=\":4\" />. In 2016 the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] received one of its largest gifts of folk art work from Margaret Z. Robson, among them were three of Edmondson's sculptures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.edu/newsdesk/releases/smithsonian-american-art-museum-acquires-major-collection-self-taught-american-art|title=Smithsonian American Art Museum Acquires Major Collection of Self-Taught American Art|last=Baptiste|first=Laura|date=December 13, 2016|website=Smithsonian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nEdmondson's art is displayed permanently at the [[The Newark Museum of Art]],  [[American Folk Art Museum]], the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum]], the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the the Montclair Musuem in New Jersey<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n== Legacy ==\nSince his death, Edmondson's work has gradually come to be highly appreciated by critics and collectors, and his sculptures garner up to $70,000-$300,000 at auction<ref name=\":4\" />. Recently in January 2016, \"A Boxer\" sold at a private auction for $785,000 the highest price ever paid <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Mayor [[Karl Dean]] opened Nashville's first arts park, named in Edmondson's honor. The park, managed by the Nashville Metropolitan Development and Housing Agency, includes sculptures by [[Thornton Dial]] and [[Lonnie Holley]] inspired by the work of William Edmondson. The park is located in a traditionally African-American neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edmondson Park dedication officially opens city's first arts park |url=http://www.nashville.gov/News-Media/News-Article/ID/3178/Edmondson-Park-dedication-officially-opens-citys-first-arts-park.aspx |website=Nashville.gov |publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> Even though the site of Edmondson's house at 1434 Fourteenth Avenue South is now a public school, it has been officially recognized with a Tennessee historical marker.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n<br />\n==Selected Recent Exhibitions==\n*Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, TN\n**''The Art of William Edmondson'' 1999 organized with the American Folk Art Museum, New York, NY\n** ''William Edmondson and Friends: Breaking the Mold, 2014''\n** [https://cheekwood.org/explore/art-4/exhibitions/past-exhibitons/edmondson-2017/ ''Visions from Above: The Life and Work of William Edmondson''], 2017\n\n== Collections with Edmondson Works ==\n\n*[[American Folk Art Museum]], New York, NY\n*[https://collections.artsmia.org/search/William%20Edmondson Minneapolis Institute of Art, Minneapolis, MN]\n*[https://www.nga.gov/features/exhibitions/outliers-and-american-vanguard-artist-biographies/william-edmondson.html The National Gallery of Art], Washington, DC\n*[https://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio-items/william-edmondson/?portfolioCats=126%2C22%2C23 Ricco Maresca Gallery, New York, NY]\n*[https://americanart.si.edu/search?query=Edmondson Smithsonian Museum of American Art], Washington, DC\n*[http://www.tnstate.edu/library/digital/EDMONDS.HTM Tennessee State LIbrary], Nashville, TN\n*[https://tnmuseum.org/temporary-exhibits/temporary%20exhibits/insearchofthenew The Tennessee State Museum], Nashville, TN\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Thompson, Lovett, Freeman, McWillie, Gundaker and Sims, ''The Art of William Edmondson'', Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, Tennessee and University Press of Mississippi, Jackson, 1999\n*The WPA Guide to Tennessee, Compiled and Written by the Federal Writers' Project of the Works Projects Administration for the State of Tennessee, The University of Tennessee Press, Knoxville, 1986\n* ''Outsider Art Sourcebook'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmondson, William}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Folk artists]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Davidson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration workers]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American sculptors]]\n[[Category:American male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Janitors]]\n", "text_old": "'''William Edmondson''' (c.1874\u20131951) was the first [[African-American]] [[folk art]] [[sculptor]] to be given a [[one-person show]] exhibition at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in [[New York City]] (1937).{{Infobox person\n| name               = William Edmondson\n| image              = File:William Edmonson.jpg\n| caption            = William Edmondson at work\n| birth_date         = December, 1874\n| birth_place        = Davidson County, Nashville, Tennessee\n| death_date         = February 7th, 1951\n| death_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| othername          = \n| birthname          = William Edmondson\n| occupation         = Sculptor\n}}\n==Biography==\nWilliam Edmondson was born sometime in December 1874 on the Compton Plantation in [[Davidson County, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Thompson|first=Robert Farris|title=The Art of William Edmondson|last2=Lovett|first2=Bobby L.|last3=Freeman|first3=Rusty|last4=McWillie|first4=Judith|date=January 1, 1999|publisher=Cheekwood Museum of Art|year=1999|isbn=1578061814|location=Cheekwood Museum of Art|pages=3-14, 15-32, 33-44, 45-60|oclc=41932532}}</ref> He did not know the date of his birth because of a fire that destroyed the family Bible.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book |last1=Edmondson |first1=William |last2=Thompson |first2=Robert Farris |last3=Freeman |first3=Rusty |title=The Art of William Edmondson |date=1999 |publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi |isbn=9781578061815 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mCOLisQ4eCkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA17 |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=10 things to know about William Edmondson |url=https://www.christies.com/features/William-Edmondson-10-things-to-know-8027-1.aspx |website=Christie's |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Edmondson was one of six children born to Orange and Jane Edmondson who had been and previously enslaved before they worked as sharecroppers. Due to privilege regarding race and color, mulattoes on the plantation were given more respectable jobs where as the Edmonson's  mainly worked in the corn fields and handled livestock. The Edmondson family worked on the plantation and earned a mere 12 dollars a month. During these times in the corn fields he would see \"angels in the clouds\" and believe it was God talking to him. <ref name=\":1\" />  Edmondson had little or no formal education. \n\nWhen his father died in late 1889,16 year-old Edmondson refused to continue to tirelessly work on the plantation and left to Nashville for work.<ref name=\":1\" /> He got a good job working at the expansive new [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railroad]] shops. After an injury sustained at the Railway shops in 1907, Edmondson took a job as a custodian at the Nashville Women's Hospital, where he worked until the hospital closed in 1931<ref name=\":2\" />. During this time Edmondson family officially resided in Nashville as his mother, Jane, was the last to leave the Compton Plantation. By age 39, his wages at Women's Hospital allowed him to buy a modest home and spacious lot in Edgehill, a segregated neighborhood in Nashville's Vanderbilt-Belmont area<ref name=\":1\" />.  Edmondson never married and he shared the home with his mother and sister, as well as, occasionally, other siblings, nieces, and nephews. With Jane's passing in 1922, Edmonson's sister, Sarah, soon became the woman of the house. It was said she would often hold family barbecues that consisted of laughter and storytelling.<ref name=\":1\" />  When the hospital closed in 1931, Edmondson picked up work at various part-time jobs and in his leisure, he could be found in his backyard sculpting and selling his vegetables.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n\nIn 1948 Edmondson stopped sculpting. On February 7th, 1951 at age seventy-six, he passed quietly in his home in Nashville, Tennessee, where illness had confined him to bed for several months. As he was the last of his siblings to pass, his five nieces and seven nephews carried out his funeral service which was held the next day<ref name=\":1\" />. William Edmondson was buried in Mount Ararat Cemetery, now [[Greenwood Cemetery (Nashville, Tennessee)]], Nashville's oldest black cemetery. Today there is no sign of Edmondson's grave marker because at the time cheap wooden caskets were used to bury African Americans. As the wood decayed it would cause the grave markers to sink into the earth.<ref name=\":1\" /> Mt. Ararat burial records of the period were lost in a fire, so his exact grave site is unknown.  \n\n== Art Career ==\n[[File:Crucifix_ca._1932-1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|369x369px|\"Crucifixion\" ca. 1932-1937, carved limestone, gift from Elizabeth Gibbons-Hanson]]\nEdmondson entered the world of sculpture at the advanced age of about 60 years old in 1934. He reported that he received a vision from God, who told him to start sculpting: \"I was out in the driveway with some old sculptures of stone when I heard a voice telling me to pick up my tools and start to work on a tombstone. I looked up in the sky and right there in the noon daylight, he hung a tombstone out for me to make. I knowed it was God telling me what to do.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Jack|first=Lindsey|title=Miracles : the sculptures of William Edmondson.|last2=Pa.)|first2=Janet Fleisher Gallery (Philadelphia|isbn=0962150630|oclc=32664611}}</ref> He carved tombstones primarily from chunks of discarded limestone from demolished buildings, which were delivered to him by wrecking companies' trucks. A signature Edmondson tombstone reflects strong large lettering carved in the stone<ref name=\":1\" />. He began his career by working on these tombstones, which he sold or gave to friends and family in the community. Soon he began carving lawn ornaments, birdbaths, and decorative sculptures. In his yard hung a sign \"Tomb-Stones. For Sale. Garden. Ornaments. Stone Work W M Edmondson\". <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Spires|first=Elizabeth|title=I Hear God Talking to Me|publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux|year=2009|isbn=9780374335281|location=New York|pages=50-52}}</ref> \n\nEdmondson's work was influenced by his [[Christianity|Christian]] faith and his membership in a nearby [[Primitive Baptist]] congregation. His sculptures are straightforward and emphatic forms ranging from one to three feet in height, many sharing his unique religious symbolism. He carved figures of biblical characters, angels, doves, turtles, eagles, rabbits, horses and other real and fanciful creatures. His sculpture ''Noah's Ark'' stood tall in the middle of his backyard. It consists for four differently carved tiers of limestone and is the only architectural work that existed in his collection.<ref name=\":1\" />, He carved local community icons such as preachers, lawyers and school teachers, celebrities of the day who were important to the [[African American]] community, such as prizefighter [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio/william-edmondson/|title=WILLIAM EDMONDSON|work=Ricco Maresca Gallery|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> He also sculpted a number of popular figures such as First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]].<ref name=\":6\" /> Edmondson also created and a small number of nude figures.<ref>''[http://www.rawvision.com/books/outsider-art-sourcebook Outsider Art Sourcebook]'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009, p.70</ref> Most of Edmonson's carved figures consisted of faces carved on a spherical base, with a small mouth resting directly under a vertical nose, following to connect to the curve of the brow. Sometimes he would decide not to carve the eyebrows and would opt to make the nose broader. It is believed he did this to achieve racial inclusion within his collection of artwork<ref name=\":1\" />. Even with versatility of his artwork, the common characteristic of an Edmondson sculpture was the overbuilt-ness of the figures carved within or from the limestone. Intentional texturing ranging between smooth, chiseled, polished or rough was present throughout the make of each sculpture.<ref name=\":1\" />  The facial technique, overbuiltness, and range in texturing can be observed in Edmonson's most well known masterpiece ''Bess and Joe'' and further with ''Mary and Martha'' <ref name=\":1\" />.  \n\nEdmondson had a large audience in Edgehill and as many of his figures were on display not only in his yard, but in that of neighbors homes and gardens.  Around 1935, about a few years into this sculpting career, [[Peabody College]] art enthusiast, Sidney Hirsch, wandered though Edgehill and caught eye of Edmondson's vast sculpture collection.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Amico|first=Michael|url=https://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/distributed/E/bo27331575.html|title=Experience|last2=Mackintosh|first2=Lucy|last3=Jane Marshall|first3=Jennifer|last4=Peters Corbett|first4=David|last5=Situ|first5=Xiao|last6=Slifkin|first6=Robert|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=2017|isbn=9780932171634|editor-last=Nemerov|editor-first=Alexander|location=Chicago|pages=102-133}}</ref> This is widely documented as Edmondson's \"discovery\" by [[Sidney Mttron Hirsch]]. Hirsch himself was a collector of African, Middle Eastern, and East Asian art and began to become one of Edmondson's greatest supporters .<ref name=\":3\" />  With this exposure, friends of Hirsch's and other fellow members of Nashville's elite bought Edmondson's sculptures for their homes, gardens, and offices, many of which were later displayed in exhibits at the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Marshall|first=Jennifer Jane|date=2017|title=Nashville, New York, Paris, and Nashville: William Edmondson, Mobilized and Unmoved|url=|journal=American Art|volume=31|pages=69-76|via=Art & Architecture Source}}</ref> Of Hirsch's friends, Alfred and Elizabeth Starr, Alfred, a managing partner of a chain of movie theaters catering to the black community, and his wife Elizabeth, a painter, also became enthusiastic patrons and supporters of Edmondson's work.  They introduced Edmondson to several artist friends, including Starr's boyhood friend Meyer (Mike) Wolfe and his wife [[Louise Dahl-Wolfe]]. Dahl-Wolfe was a photographer who had recently begun work for ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'' fashion magazine in [[New York City|New York]]. She made over a hundred of photographs of Edmondson's at work in his backyard shop, which she presented to the editor of Harper's Bazaar''.'' She attempted to publish his work but newspaper chain mogul [[William Randolph Hearst]], had a prejudice against showing Negro art as he seen them as nothing other than servants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/william-edmondson-down-home-artist-forging-beauty-stone|title=William Edmondson, a down home artist forging beauty from stone|work=aaregistry.org|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=\":4\" /> She then brought Edmondson's work to the attention of fellow Tennessean Thomas Mabry and his boss [[Alfred Barr]], the director of the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA)<ref name=\":1\" />.  \n\nEdmondson's career lasted for about fifteen years. His work never commanded large sums during his lifetime. In 1939 and again in 1941, he worked under the [[Works Progress Administration]], a government sponsored relief program that included artists. In the late 1940s, his health began to fail and his artistic production slowed. Edmondson professed to be uninterested in fame, and he appears to have struggled financially for the final years of his life. He is believed to have created about 300 works during his working lifetime.  \n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Bird_ca._1937.jpg|alt=|thumb|291x291px|Bird ca. 1937, carved limestone, gift from Margaret Z. Robson]]\nEdmondson was given a one-man show, the first by an African American artist, at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] from October 20th to December 1st 1937<ref name=\":1\" />. In 1938, through MoMA's influence, William Edmondson's sculpture was included in the \"Three Centuries of Art in the United States\" in [[Paris, France|Paris]]. Interest in his work on the national and international stage was short-lived, and he was viewed primarily as a novelty, or exemplar of the \"primitive\" race-memory of an untutored, naive old Negro stone carver. Locally, Alfred Starr continued to promote Edmondson's work to his artistic friends and acquaintances, who bought work directly from Edmondson's \"sculpture yard\" or through the local Lyzon Gallery. Starr introduced the famed modernist photographer [[Edward Weston]] to Edmondson in 1941, and Weston made several striking photographs of Edmondson at work in his shop and yard. Also in 1941, he received the only other solo show accorded during his lifetime, at the Nashville Art Gallery.\n\nAfter very sporadic exhibition through the 1950s and 1960s (mostly as part of \"folk art\" exhibits), collector [[Edmund Fuller]] wrote a biography of Edmondson which was published in 1973. His sculpture was included in the influential \"[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]\" exhibition curated by [[Fisk University]] Art Department chairman [[David C. Driskell]] in 1976.  In 1981 the new [[Tennessee State Museum]] opened with a permanent solo exhibition with six of Edmondson's sculptures featuring loaned sculptures from Elizabeth Starr's personal collection<ref name=\":1\" />, and the essays in the accompanying catalog sought to elevate appreciation of Edmondson's work as fine art. Through the 1980s and 1990s Edmondson's sculptures were exhibited extensively, though often in the limiting context of the labels \"outsider\", \"folk art\", \"self-taught\", and \"naive\". In 1999, Nashville's [[Cheekwood Botanical Garden and Museum of Art|Cheekwood Museum of Art]] mounted a major traveling retrospective exhibition and catalog that included in-depth biographical and critical essays on his life and work This exhibit also sculptures from Elizabeth Starrs personal collection of which she donated to the museum.<ref name=\":1\" /> A 2006 exhibition, \"William Edmondson, Bill Traylor, and the Modernist Impulse,\" paired Edmondson with another well-known self-taught artist and argued for Edmondson's acceptance as an artist without limiting labels. This exhibit displeayed twenty-one of Edmondon's sculptures which is the largest collection of Edmondson's art in the country<ref name=\":4\" />. In 2016 the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] received one of its largest gifts of folk art work from Margaret Z. Robson, among them were three of Edmondson's sculptures<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.edu/newsdesk/releases/smithsonian-american-art-museum-acquires-major-collection-self-taught-american-art|title=Smithsonian American Art Museum Acquires Major Collection of Self-Taught American Art|last=Baptiste|first=Laura|date=December 13, 2016|website=Smithsonian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. \n\nCurrently Edmondson's art is displayed permanently at the [[The Newark Museum of Art]],  [[American Folk Art Museum]], the [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], the [[Philadelphia Museum of Art]], the [[Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Museum]], the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] and the the Montclair Musuem in New Jersey<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n<br />\n\n== Legacy ==\nSince his death, Edmondson's work has gradually come to be highly appreciated by critics and collectors, and his sculptures garner up to $70,000-$300,000 at auction<ref name=\":4\" />. Recently in January 2016, \"A Boxer\" sold at a private auction for $785,000 the highest price ever paid <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\nOn August 20, 2014, Mayor [[Karl Dean]] opened Nashville's first arts park, named in Edmondson's honor. The park, managed by the Nashville Metropolitan Development and Housing Agency, includes sculptures by [[Thornton Dial]] and [[Lonnie Holley]] inspired by the work of William Edmondson. The park is located in a traditionally African-American neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edmondson Park dedication officially opens city's first arts park |url=http://www.nashville.gov/News-Media/News-Article/ID/3178/Edmondson-Park-dedication-officially-opens-citys-first-arts-park.aspx |website=Nashville.gov |publisher=Metropolitan Government of Nashville and Davidson County |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref> Even though the site of Edmondson's house at 1434 Fourteenth Avenue South is now a public school, it has been officially recognized with a Tennessee historical marker.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n<br />\n==Selected Recent Exhibitions==\n*Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, TN\n**''The Art of William Edmondson'' 1999 organized with the American Folk Art Museum, New York, NY\n** ''William Edmondson and Friends: Breaking the Mold, 2014''\n** [https://cheekwood.org/explore/art-4/exhibitions/past-exhibitons/edmondson-2017/ ''Visions from Above: The Life and Work of William Edmondson''], 2017\n\n== Collections with Edmondson Works ==\n\n*[[American Folk Art Museum]], New York, NY\n*[https://collections.artsmia.org/search/William%20Edmondson Minneapolis Institute of Art, Minneapolis, MN]\n*[https://www.nga.gov/features/exhibitions/outliers-and-american-vanguard-artist-biographies/william-edmondson.html The National Gallery of Art], Washington, DC\n*[https://www.riccomaresca.com/portfolio-items/william-edmondson/?portfolioCats=126%2C22%2C23 Ricco Maresca Gallery, New York, NY]\n*[https://americanart.si.edu/search?query=Edmondson Smithsonian Museum of American Art], Washington, DC\n*[http://www.tnstate.edu/library/digital/EDMONDS.HTM Tennessee State LIbrary], Nashville, TN\n*[https://tnmuseum.org/temporary-exhibits/temporary%20exhibits/insearchofthenew The Tennessee State Museum], Nashville, TN\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n*Thompson, Lovett, Freeman, McWillie, Gundaker and Sims, ''The Art of William Edmondson'', Cheekwood Museum of Art, Nashville, Tennessee and University Press of Mississippi, Jackson, 1999\n*The WPA Guide to Tennessee, Compiled and Written by the Federal Writers' Project of the Works Projects Administration for the State of Tennessee, The University of Tennessee Press, Knoxville, 1986\n* ''Outsider Art Sourcebook'', ed. John Maizels, Raw Vision, Watford, 2009\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edmondson, William}}\n[[Category:1882 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:Folk artists]]\n[[Category:African-American artists]]\n[[Category:People from Davidson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Works Progress Administration workers]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:20th-century American sculptors]]\n[[Category:American male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Janitors]]\n", "name_user": "Dmbailey5", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Edmondson"}
{"title_page": "Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 25, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] that ran from 1990 to 1996.\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992, a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|starring =\n|country = United States\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]]\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1990}}\n|last_aired = {{End date|1993}}\n|num_episodes = 69 (SportsChannel America)<br>24 (ESPN2)\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year deal with national cable network [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990 and aired on Monday nights. Reruns of the program, along with sporadic new episodes, continued airing on the network through 1993.\n\nIn 1991, Herb Abrams was owed money by Steve Ray and wrongly suspected that Ray was sleeping with his wife. On May 10, 1991 during a television taping at the [[New York Penta]], Abrams paid [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]] an extra $100 for the night to break Ray's nose during their match. Ray would years later claim this was a Worked Shoot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nIn 1995, existing episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 episodes re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]]<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref> between January and March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref> ESPN Classic started re-airing these episodes on February 4, 2009. [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)| ]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 25, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] that ran from 1990 to 1996.\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992, a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|starring =\n|country = United States\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]]\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1990}}\n|last_aired = {{End date|1993}}\n|num_episodes = 69 (SportsChannel America)<br>24 (ESPN2)\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year deal with national cable network [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990 and aired on Monday nights. Reruns of the program, along with sporadic new episodes, continued airing on the network through 1993.\n\nIn 1991, Herb Abrams was owed money by Steve Ray and wrongly suspected that Ray was sleeping with his wife. On May 10, 1991 during a television taping at the [[New York Penta]], Abrams paid [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]] an extra $100 for the night to break Ray's nose during their match. Ray would years later claim this was a Worked Shoot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nIn 1995, existing episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 episodes re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]]<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref> between January and March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref> ESPN Classic started re-airing these episodes on February 4, 2009. [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)| ]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "name_user": "TheNewMinistry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecurring segments:formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Wrestling_Federation_(Herb_Abrams)"}
{"title_page": "Ian Rankin", "text_new": "{{About||the Scottish footballer|Ian Rankin (footballer)|the Canadian politician|Iain Rankin (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n | name        = Ian Rankin\n | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FRSE|FRSL}}\n | image       = IanRankin.jpg\n | imagesize   =\n | caption     = Ian Rankin in August 2007\n | pseudonym   = Jack Harvey\n | birth_name  = Ian James Rankin\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|04|28|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Cardenden]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n | residence   = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland  \n | death_date  =\n | death_place =\n | occupation  = Novelist\n | nationality =  Scottish\n | period      = 1984\u2013present\n | genre       = [[Crime fiction]]\n | subject     =\n | notableworks = [[DI John Rebus]] novels<br/>Malcolm Fox novels<br/>''[[Dark Entries (comics)|Dark Entries]]''\n | signature   =\n | website     = {{URL|http://www.ianrankin.net}}\n | spouse   = {{marriage|Miranda Harvey|1986}}\n | children = 2\n | module = {{Listen |embed= yes |filename= Ian_Rankin_BBC_Radio4_Desert_Island_Discs_6_Nov_2011_b016vh1b.flac |title= Ian Rankin's voice |type= speech |description= from the BBC programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', 6 November 2011.<ref>{{Cite episode |title= Ian Rankin |series= Desert Island Discs |serieslink= Desert Island Discs |url= http://bbc.co.uk/programmes/b016vh1b |station= [[BBC Radio 4]] |date= 6 November 2011 |accessdate= 18 January 2014 }}</ref> }}\n}}\n'''Ian James Rankin''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FRSE|FRSL}} (born 28 April 1960) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] crime writer, best known for his [[Inspector Rebus]] novels.\n\n==Early life==\nRankin was born in [[Cardenden]], Fife. His father, James, owned a grocery shop, and his mother, Isobel, worked in a school canteen.<ref name = Sturgis>{{cite news|last1=Sturgis|first1=India|title=If I Could See Me Now... What Your Younger Self Would Make of you Today \u2013 Ian Rankin|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|issue = Weekend supplement |date=26 December 2015}}</ref> He was educated at [[Beath High School]], [[Cowdenbeath]]. His parents were horrified when he then chose to study literature at university, as they had expected him to study for a trade.<ref name = Sturgis/> Encouraged by his English teacher, he persisted and graduated in 1982 from the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he also worked on a doctorate on [[Muriel Spark]] but did not complete it.<ref name = BBC2>{{cite web|title=Ian Rankin 1960-  Biography|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mr8yj/profiles/ian-rankin|website=BBC Two;  Writing Scotland|accessdate=27 December 2015|date=September 2004}}</ref> He has taught at the university and retains an involvement with the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]]. He lived in [[Tottenham]], London, for four years and then rural France for six while he developed his career as a novelist.<ref>Rankin, I. (1998) ''Tooth & Nail''. London: Orion. p. vii.</ref> Before becoming a full-time novelist, he worked as a grape picker, [[swineherd]], taxman, alcohol researcher, hi-fi journalist, college secretary and punk musician in a band called the Dancing Pigs.<ref>[http://www.januarymagazine.com/profiles/ianrankin.html \"Profile: Ian Rankin\"], ''January Magazine''</ref><ref>[http://www.bookslut.com/features/2005_04_005009.php \"Ian Rankin\"], Bookslut, April 2005.</ref><ref name = Sturgis/>\n\n==Career==\nRankin did not set out to be a [[crime writer]]. He thought his first novels, ''[[Knots and Crosses]]'' and ''[[Hide and Seek (Ian Rankin novel)|Hide and Seek]]'', were mainstream books, more in keeping with the Scottish traditions of [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and even [[Muriel Spark]]. He was disconcerted by their classification as genre fiction. The [[List of Scottish novelists|Scottish novelist]] [[Allan Massie]], who tutored Rankin while Massie was writer-in-residence at the University of Edinburgh, reassured him by saying, \"Do you think [[John Buchan]] ever worried about whether he was writing literature or not?\"<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news|author=Barnett, Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/dec/11/ian-rankin-portrait|newspaper=The Guardian|title=Ian Rankin, Author\u2014Portrait of the Artist|date=11 December 2012|accessdate= 8 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nRankin's [[Inspector Rebus]] novels are set mainly in Edinburgh. They are considered major contributions to the [[tartan noir]] genre. Ten of the novels were adapted as a [[Rebus (TV)|television series]] on ITV, starring [[John Hannah (actor)|John Hannah]] as Rebus in series 1 and 2 and [[Ken Stott]] in that role in series 3\u20135.\n\nIn 2009, Rankin donated the short story \"Fieldwork\" to [[Oxfam]]'s ''[[Ox-Tales]]'' project, four collections of UK stories written by 38 authors. Rankin's story was published in the ''Earth'' collection.<ref name=\"Ox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/shop/content/books/books_oxtales.html |title=Ox-Tales |publisher=Oxfam.org.uk |date= |access-date=4 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520182004/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/shop/content/books/books_oxtales.html |archive-date=20 May 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n[[File:Ian Rankin signing Dark Entries in Forbidden Planet Edinburgh 06.jpg|thumb|Rankin signing copies of his debut graphic novel, ''Dark Entries'', in the Edinburgh [[Forbidden Planet]] International store in December 2009.]]\n\nIn 2009 Rankin stated on [[Radio Five Live]] that he would start work on a five- or six-issue run on the comic book ''[[Hellblazer]]'', although he may turn the story into a stand-alone [[graphic novel]] instead. The Vertigo Comics panel at [[WonderCon]] 2009 confirmed that the story would be published as a [[graphic novel]], ''[[Dark Entries (comics)|Dark Entries]]'', the second release from the company's [[Vertigo Crime]] imprint.<ref name=\"DarkEntries\">{{cite web |title = WC: Vertigo - Innovative and Provocative |date=1 March 2009 |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=20252 |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsarama.com/comics/030925-Vertigo-Rankin.html |title=Starting Vertigo's Crime Line: Ian Rankin on Dark Entries |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |date=25 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Duin |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2009/04/ian_rankin_vs_brian_azzarello.html |title=Ian Rankin vs. Brian Azzarello |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Rankin co-wrote the play ''[[Dark Road (play)|Dark Road]]'' with Mark Thomson, the artistic director of the [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.list.co.uk/article/54887-edinburgh-lyceums-mark-thomson-discusses-dark-road-the-first-play-by-ian-rankin/ | title=Mark Thomson Discusses Dark Road, the First Play by Ian Rankin | publisher=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] | work=list.co.uk | date=17 September 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/liam-rudden-lyceum-aims-for-top-rankin-with-dark-road-1-2915455 | title=Lyceum Aims for Top Rankin with Dark Road | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=1 May 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> The play, which marked Rankin's play-writing debut,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/ian-rankin-turns-his-pen-from-rebus-to-stage-play.20959653 | title=Ian Rankin Turns His Pen from Rebus to Stage Play | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=1 May 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> premiered at the Lyceum Theatre, [[Edinburgh]], in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.stv.tv/east-central/223477-rebus-author-ian-rankin-debuts-first-play-as-part-of-lyceum-new-season/ | title=The Lyceum to Host Ian Rankin's Debut Play as Part of New Season | publisher=[[Scottish Television|STV]] | work=news.stv.tv | date=30 April 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233201/http://news.stv.tv/east-central/223477-rebus-author-ian-rankin-debuts-first-play-as-part-of-lyceum-new-season/ | archive-date=3 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nRankin is a regular contributor to the [[BBC Two]] arts programme ''Newsnight Review''. His 3-part documentary series on the subject of [[evil]] was broadcast on [[Channel 4]] in December 2002. In 2005 he presented a 30-minute documentary on [[BBC Four]] called ''Rankin on the Staircase'', in which he investigated the relationship between real-life cases and crime fiction.  It was loosely based on the [[Michael Peterson (author and convicted criminal)|Michael Peterson]] murder case, as covered in Jean-Xavier Lestrade's documentary series ''Death on the Staircase''. The same year he collaborated with folk musician [[Jackie Leven]] on the album ''Jackie Leven Said''.\n\nIn 2007, Rankin appeared in programmes for BBC Four exploring the origins of his alter-ego character, [[John Rebus]]. Titled \"Ian Rankin's Hidden Edinburgh\" and \"Ian Rankin Investigates Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde,\" Rankin looks at the origins of the character and the events that led to his creation.\n\nIn the TV show ''[[Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations]]'', he takes a trip through Edinburgh with writer/cook [[Anthony Bourdain]].\n\n== Music ==\nRankin is the singer in the six-piece band Best Picture, formed by journalists Kenny Farquharson (''The Times'') and Euan McColl (''The Scotsman'') in 2017, and featuring [[The Bluebells|Bobby Bluebell]] on guitar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farquharson |first1=Kenny |title=The six dads about to rock salute you |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-six-dads-about-to-rock-salute-you-t3x52wf5j |accessdate=28 July 2018 |newspaper=The Times |date=24 October 2017}}</ref>  They released a single \"Isabelle\" on [[Oriel Records]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ross |first1=Peter |title=Rebus and roll: Ian Rankin\u2019s new gig as a \u2018dad rock\u2019 singer |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/shortcuts/2017/oct/15/rebus-and-roll-ian-rankin-new-gig-as-a-dad-rock-singer |accessdate=28 July 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 October 2017}}</ref>  They made their live debut at the [[Kendal Calling]] music festival on 28 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Picture - Kendal Calling |url=https://www.kendalcalling.co.uk/artists/best-picture |website=Kendal Calling |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in [[Edinburgh]] with his wife, Miranda (n\u00e9e Harvey), whom he met at university and married in 1986, and their two sons: John Morgan \"Jack\" Harvey-Rankin (born 1992) and Christopher Connor \"Kit\" Harvey-Rankin (born 1994). They lived for a number of years in the [[Merchiston]]/[[Morningside, Edinburgh|Morningside]] area,<ref name=\"Williams-Akoto\">{{cite news |last1=Williams-Akoto |first1=Tessa |title=My Home: Ian Rankin, crime writer |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/property/house-and-home/property/my-home-ian-rankin-crime-writer-317152.html |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=5 October 2005}}</ref> near the authors [[JK Rowling]], [[Alexander McCall Smith]] and [[Kate Atkinson]],<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite news |last1=Mitchell |first1=Hilary |title=Welcome to the 'Writer's Block' - spotlight on exclusive Edinburgh area after Ian Rankin sells house |url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/news/edinburgh-news/welcome-writers-block-spotlight-exclusive-16257774 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Edinburgh Live |date=10 May 2019}}</ref> before moving to a penthouse flat in the former Royal Infirmary building in Quartermile.<ref name=\"MacDonald\">{{cite news |last1=MacDonald |first1=Stuart |title=Author Ian Rankin cashes in on Edinburgh mansion after \u00a32.1 million sale |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/lifestyle/author-ian-rankin-cashes-edinburgh-mansion-after-ps21-million-sale-546995 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The couple also own a house in [[Cromarty]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]].<ref name=\"Reece\">{{cite news |last1=Reece |first1=Alex |title=My Coast: Ian Rankin |url=https://www.coastmagazine.co.uk/content/my-coast-ian-rankin |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Coast Magazine}}</ref> Rankin appears as a character in McCall Smith's 2004 novel, ''[[44 Scotland Street]]''.\n\nIn 2011 [[Scottish book sculptures|a group of ten book sculptures]] were deposited around Edinburgh as gifts to cultural institutions and the people of the city. Many of the sculptures made reference to the work of Rankin, and an eleventh sculpture was a personal gift to him.<ref name=CS>{{cite news|title=Mysterious paper sculptures |url=http://thisiscentralstation.com/featured/mysterious-paper-sculptures/|work=Central Stn|first=Chris|last=Scott|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1988 Elected [[Hawthornden Castle|Hawthornden]] Fellow<ref name=\"bfs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.booksfromscotland.com/Authors/Ian-Rankin|publisher=BooksfromScotland.com |title=Ian Rankin |date=|accessdate= 7 January 2013}}</ref>\n*1991 Chandler-[[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Award<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*1994 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Short Story Dagger for ''A Deep Hole''<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite news |url=http://literature.britishcouncil.org/ian-rankin |publisher=The British Council |title=Ian Rankin |date= |accessdate=7 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605221310/http://literature.britishcouncil.org/ian-rankin |archive-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*1996 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Short Story Dagger for ''Herbert in Motion'' in ''Perfectly Criminal''<ref name=\"CWA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/short.html|publisher=Crime Writers Association|title=The CWA Short Story Dagger|date=5 July 2012|access-date=7 January 