ies (comics)|Dark Entries]]'' || ''Vertigo Crime'' featuring [[John Constantine]]\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[The Impossible Dead]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ianrankin.net/pages/news/index.asp?NewsID=53 |title=Ian Rankin latest news, Exit Music, Ian Rankin Rebus novels, Doors Open novel, Books Direct Crime Thriller of the Year, Galaxy British Book Awards |publisher=Ianrankin.net |date= |accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> || 2nd Malcolm Fox novel\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Standing in Another Man's Grave]]''<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/2012/06/05/rebus-is-back-ian-rankin-reveals-his-famous-detective-will-return-in-new-novel-86908-23886972/ | title=Rebus is back! Ian Rankin reveals his famous detective will return in new novel | newspaper=[[Daily Record (Scotland)]] | date=5 June 2012 | accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> || 18th Inspector Rebus & 3rd Malcolm Fox novel\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Saints of the Shadow Bible]]'' || 19th Inspector Rebus & 4th Malcolm Fox novel\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014 || ''Dark Road'' || Stage play, with [[Mark Thomson]]\n|-\n| ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories || Short stories\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Even Dogs in the Wild]]'' || 20th Rebus & 5th Malcolm Fox novel\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016 || ''The Travelling Companion'' || Limited edition bibliomystery; No 26 in a series of short stories by crime writers [https://web.archive.org/web/20180724160946/https://www.bookgrail.com/store/death-sentences/ Death Sentences]\n|-\n| ''[[Rather Be the Devil]]'' || 21st Rebus & 6th Malcolm Fox novel\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018 || ''[[Rebus: Long Shadows]]'' || Stage play, with [[Rona Munro]] (part of the Inspector Rebus series)\n|-\n| ''[[In a House of Lies]]'' || 22nd Rebus & 7th Malcolm Fox novel\n|}\n\n==Other publications==\n'''Edited anthology'''\n* ''Criminal Minded'' (2000) (edited and with an introduction by Rankin)\n'''Recordings'''\n* ''Jackie Leven Said'' (Cooking vinyl, 2005), with [[Jackie Leven]]\n* ''The Sixth Stone'' (CD, 2007), with [[Aidan Moffat]], on ''[[Ballads of the Book]]''\n* ''This Has Been the Death of Us'' (7th Realm Of Teenage Heaven, 2009), with [[Saint Jude's Infirmary]]\n* ''The Third Gentleman'' (BBC Broadcast 25 October 1997. 87mins). Black comedy set in 1790s Edinburgh.\n\n'''Graphic novels'''\n*'' [[Dark Entries (comics)|Dark Entries]]'' (September 2009) with art by [[Werther Dell'Edera]]. Published by [[Vertigo Crime]] and starring [[John Constantine]] of [[Hellblazer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ianrankin.net/pages/content/index.asp?PageID=97 |title=Ian Rankin Newsletter |publisher=Ianrankin.net |date= |accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/comics/080815-VertigoCrime.html |title=Karen Berger On The Vertigo Crime Line |publisher=Newsarama.com |date= |accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Graphic novella'''\n* ''The Lie Factory'', illustrated by Tim Truman. Published as part of a CD package, ''Kickback City'', featuring [[Rory Gallagher]] songs fictionalized in the novella and with narration by [[Aidan Quinn]]\n\n'''Opera'''\n* ''Gesualdo'', with [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]] (2008)\n'''Short stories'''\n* \"Summer Rites\" (1984) (published in ''Cencrastus'', No. 18 - actually a section of Rankin's first novel)\n* [http://www.theshortstory.org.uk/stories/index.php4?storyid=9 \"An Afternoon\"] (1984) (published in ''[[Association for Scottish Literary Studies#New Writing Scotland|New Writing Scotland No. 2]]'') (slightly revised version published in ''OxCrimes'', 2014)\n* \"Voyeurism\" (1985) (published in ''New Writing Scotland No. 3'')\n* \"Colony\" (1986) (published in ''New Writing Scotland No. 4'')\n* \"Scarab\" (1986) (published in ''Scottish Short Stories 1986'')\n* \"Territory\" (1987) (published in ''Scottish Short Stories 1987'')\n* \"Remembrance\" (1988) (published in ''Cencrastus'', Spring)\n* \"Playback\" (1990) (Rebus; published in Winter's Crime 22; reprinted in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'', 1992)\n* \"Talk Show\" (1991) (Rebus; published in ''Winter's Crimes'' 23)\n* \"The Dean Curse\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Being Frank\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Concrete Evidence\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Seeing Things\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"A Good Hanging\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Tit for Tat\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Not Provan\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Sunday\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Auld Lang Syne\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"The Gentlemen's Club\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Monstrous Trumpet\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"In the Frame\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''Winter's Crimes'' 24)\n* \"Trip Trap\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''1st Culprit'')\n* \"Marked for Death\" (1992) (published in ''Constable New Crimes'' 1)\n* \"Well Shot\" (1993) (Rebus; published in ''2nd Culprit''; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Video, Nasty\" (1993) (published in ''Constable New Crimes 2'')\n* \"Castle Dangerous\" (1993) (Rebus; published in ''[[Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine]]'', ''EQMM'', October)\n* \"Someone Got to Eddie\" (1994) (published in ''3rd Culprit'')\n* \"Facing the Music\" (1994) (Rebus; published in ''Midwinter Mysteries'' 4)\n* \"A Deep Hole\" (1994) (published in ''London Noir'')\n* \"The Serpent's Back\" (1995) (published in ''Midwinter Mysteries'' 5)\n* \"Adventures in Babysitting\" (1995) (published in ''No Alibi'' and in ''Master's Choice Two'')\n* \"Principles of Accounts\" (1995) (published in ''EQMM'', August)\n* \"Window of Opportunity\" (1995) (Rebus, published in ''EQMM'', December)\n* \"Natural Selection\" (1996) (published in ''Fresh Blood'')\n* \"Herbert in Motion\" (1996) (published in ''Perfectly Criminal'')<ref name=\"CWA\"/>\n* \"The Wider Scheme\" (1996) (published in ''EQMM'', August)\n* \"My Shopping Day\" (1997) (Rebus; published in ''Herbert in Motion & Other Stories'' [limited edition chapbook of 200 copies]; not included in the UK edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'', but included in the U.S. edition)\n* \"No. 79\" (1997) (published in Herbert in Motion & Other Stories)\n* \"Glimmer\" (1998) (published in ''Blue Lightning'')\n* \"Unknown Pleasures\" (1998) (published in ''Mean Time'')\n* \"Detective Novels: The Pact Between Authors and Readers\" (1998) (article; published in ''The Writer'', December)\n* \"[[Death is Not the End]]\" (1998) (novella later expanded into ''Dead Souls'')\n* \"The Missing\" (1999) (published in ''Crime Wave'', March)\n* \"Get Shortie\" (1999) (Rebus; published in ''Crime Wave 2, Deepest Red'', June; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Acid Test\" (1999) (Rebus; published in ''EQMM'', August; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Hanged Man\" (1999) (published in ''Something Wicked'' (UK) and ''EQMM'', September/October)\n* \"The Only True Comedian\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', February)\n* \"Unlucky in Love, Unlucky at Cards\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', March)\n* \"The Confession\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', June)\n* \"The Slab Boys\" (2000) (published in ''Scenes of Crime'')\n* \"No Sanity Clause\" (2000) (Rebus; originally titled \"Father Christmas's Revenge, published in ''The Daily Telegraph'', December)\n* \"Tell Me Who to Kill\" (2003) (Rebus; published in ''Mysterious Pleasures'')\n* \"Saint Nicked\" (2003/2004) (published in ''The Radio Times'', 21 December 2003 & 4 January 2004)\n* \"Soft Spot\" (2005) (published in ''Dangerous Women'')\n* \"Showtime\" (2005) (published in ''One City'')\n* \"Not Just another Saturday\" (August 2005) (written for SNIP, a charity organisation; people in attendance of the event were provided with a \"typescript\" of the story)\n* \"Atonement\" (2005) (written for the anthology ''Complete Short Stories'', which combined the contents of ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'' and ''Beggar's Banquet'', but was far from \"Complete\")\n* \"Sinner: justified\" (2006) (published in ''Superhumanatural'')\n* \"Graduation Day\" (2006) (published in ''Murder in the Rough'')\n* \"Fieldwork\" (2009) (published in ''[[Ox-Tales]]'')<ref name=\"Ox\"/>\n* \"Penalty Clause\" (2010) (Rebus; published in ''Mail on Sunday'', December)\n* \"The Very Last Drop\" (2013) (Rebus; written to read aloud at an Edinburgh charity event to help the work of Royal Blind; published in the US and UK editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Dead and Buried\" (2013) (Rebus; published with ''Saints of the Shadow Bible'')\n* \"In the Nick of Time\" (2014) (Rebus; published in ''Face Off'')\n* \"The Passenger\" (2014) (Rebus; published in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"A Three-Pint Problem\" (2014) (Rebus; published in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Cinders\" (2015) (Rebus; published in the US edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Travelling Companion\" (2015) (novella, published by the Mysterious Bookshop, NYC; signed, lettered limited cloth edition of 26 copies and 100 numbered copies; softcover edition of 1,000 copies; published in the UK in 2016 by Head of Zeus Ltd, London)\n* \"Meet & Greet\" (2015) (published in ''The Strand'' XLVI)\n* \"The Kill Fee\" (2015) (published in ''The New Statesman'' December 18, 2015\u2014January 8, 2016)\n* \"Cafferty's Day\" (2016) (Rebus; published with ''Rather be the Devil'')\n* \"Charades\" (2017) (Rebus; published in ''Country Life'' December 13/20)\n\n'''Other'''\n* \"Oxford Bar\" (2007) (Essay published in the anthology ''How I Write: The Secret Lives of Authors'')<ref name=\"isfd\">{{cite web|author=|publisher=[[Internet Speculative Fiction Database]]|date=|title=Publication Listing for ''How I Write:The Secret Lives of Authors''|accessdate=12 January 2013|url=http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?312245}}</ref>\n* \"John Rebus\" (2007) (''Mysterious Profile #8'', a chapbook published by the Mysterious Bookshop in NYC in a signed limited hardcover edition of 100 copies and 1,000 softcover copies; reprinted in the UK edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'' as \"Rankin on Rebus\")\n* Ian Rankin interviews Arthur Conan Doyle (2013), published in ''Dead Interviews''<ref>{{cite book |author= Dan Crowe (editor) |coauthors=  |title= Dead Interviews: Living Writers Meet Dead Icons |year= 2013 |publisher= Granta, London |pp= [https://archive.org/details/deadinterviewsli0000unse/page/143 143\u2013153] |quote=  |url= https://archive.org/details/deadinterviewsli0000unse/page/143 |isbn= 978-1-84708-827-7 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n*Alegre, Sara Martin., [https://archive.is/20130624210411/http://mcfarland.metapress.com/content/a68500688130n975/ \"Aging in F(r)iendship: 'Big Ger' Cafferty and John Rebus\"], in ''Clues: A Journal of Detection'' 29.2 (2011): 73\u201382.\n*Horsley, Lee, ''The Noir Thriller'' (Houndmills & New York: Palgrave, 2001).\n*Lanchester, John, \"Rebusworld\", in ''London Review of Books'' 22.9 (27 April 2000), pp.&nbsp;18\u201320.\n*[[John Lennard|Lennard, John]], \"Ian Rankin\", in Jay Parini, ed., ''British Writers Supplement X'' (New York & London: Charles Scribner's Sons, 2004), pp.&nbsp;243\u201360\n*MacDonald, Erin E., [https://archive.is/20130624210353/http://mcfarland.metapress.com/content/31vjn9282660450w/ \"Ghosts and Skeletons: Metaphors of Guilty History in Ian Rankin's Rebus Series\"], in ''Clues: A Journal of Detection'' 30.2 (2012): 67\u201375.\n*Mandel, Ernest, ''Delightful Murder: A Social History of the Crime Story'' (Leichhardt, NSW, & London: Pluto Press, 1984).\n*Marshall, Rodney, ''Blurred Boundaries: Rankin's Rebus'' (Amazon, 2012)\n* Nicol, Christopher, \"Ian Rankin's 'Black & Blue'\", Scotnote No.24 (Glasgow: ASLS Publications, 2008)\n*Ogle, Tina, \"Crime on Screen\", in ''The Observer'' (London), 16 April 2000, Screen p.&nbsp;8.\n*Plain, Gill, ''Ian Rankin\u2019s Black and Blue'' (London & New York: Continuum, 2002)\n*Plain, Gillian, \"Ian Rankin: A Bibliography\", in ''Crime Time'' 28 (2002), pp.&nbsp;16\u201320.\n*Robinson, David, \"Mystery Man: In Search of the real Ian Rankin\", in ''The Scotsman'' 10 March 2001, S2Weekend, pp.&nbsp;1\u20134.\n*Rowland, Susan, \"Gothic Crimes: A Literature of Terror and Horror\", in ''From Agatha Christie to Ruth Rendell'' (Houndmills & New York: Palgrave, 2001), pp.&nbsp;110\u201334.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Ian Rankin}}\n* Ian Rankin {{official website|http://www.ianrankin.net}}\n* {{IMDb name|0710256}}\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/authors/author/0,5917,-163,00.html Guardian Books profile], with links to further articles.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/talesofonecity#p/search/5/2K15Gxy_FvU Ian Rankin at Edinburgh Central Library, Oct 2010] (video interview in several parts)\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/2006/TRAVEL/02/03/edinburgh.qa/ CNN interview with Ian Rankin]\n* [http://www.edrants.com/segundo/ian-rankin-bss-390/ 2011 radio interview] at [[The Bat Segundo Show]] (1 hour)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517015653/http://www.booksfromscotland.com/Authors/Ian-Rankin/Interview-Exit-Music Two BooksfromScotland.com interviews with Ian Rankin]\n* [http://podcast.radionz.co.nz/ntn/ntn-20130226-1008-feature_guest_-_ian_rankin-048.mp3 Radio Interview on RadioNZ's Nine to Noon Show 26 February 2013]\n\n{{Rebus novels}}\n{{Ian Rankin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rankin, Ian}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cardenden]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish comics writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cartier Diamond Dagger winners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Detection Club]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beath High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Scottish male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Tartan Noir writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the Scottish footballer|Ian Rankin (footballer)|the Canadian politician|Iain Rankin (politician)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox writer\n | name        = Ian Rankin\n | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FRSE|FRSL}}\n | image       = IanRankin.jpg\n | imagesize   =\n | caption     = Ian Rankin in August 2007\n | pseudonym   = Jack Harvey\n | birth_name  = Ian James Rankin\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|04|28|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Cardenden]], [[Fife]], Scotland\n | residence   = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland  \n | death_date  =\n | death_place =\n | occupation  = Novelist\n | nationality =  Scottish\n | period      = 1984\u2013present\n | genre       = [[Crime fiction]]\n | subject     =\n | notableworks = [[DI John Rebus]] novels<br/>Malcolm Fox novels<br/>''[[Dark Entries (comics)|Dark Entries]]''\n | signature   =\n | website     = {{URL|http://www.ianrankin.net}}\n | spouse   = {{marriage|Miranda Harvey|1986}}\n | children = 2\n | module = {{Listen |embed= yes |filename= Ian_Rankin_BBC_Radio4_Desert_Island_Discs_6_Nov_2011_b016vh1b.flac |title= Ian Rankin's voice |type= speech |description= from the BBC programme ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', 6 November 2011.<ref>{{Cite episode |title= Ian Rankin |series= Desert Island Discs |serieslink= Desert Island Discs |url= http://bbc.co.uk/programmes/b016vh1b |station= [[BBC Radio 4]] |date= 6 November 2011 |accessdate= 18 January 2014 }}</ref> }}\n}}\n'''Ian James Rankin''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FRSE|FRSL}} (born 28 April 1960) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] crime writer, best known for his [[Inspector Rebus]] novels.\n\n==Early life==\nRankin was born in [[Cardenden]], Fife. His father, James, owned a grocery shop, and his mother, Isobel, worked in a school canteen.<ref name = Sturgis>{{cite news|last1=Sturgis|first1=India|title=If I Could See Me Now... What Your Younger Self Would Make of you Today \u2013 Ian Rankin|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|issue = Weekend supplement |date=26 December 2015}}</ref> He was educated at [[Beath High School]], [[Cowdenbeath]]. His parents were horrified when he then chose to study literature at university, as they had expected him to study for a trade.<ref name = Sturgis/> Encouraged by his English teacher, he persisted and graduated in 1982 from the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he also worked on a doctorate on [[Muriel Spark]] but did not complete it.<ref name = BBC2>{{cite web|title=Ian Rankin 1960-  Biography|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00mr8yj/profiles/ian-rankin|website=BBC Two;  Writing Scotland|accessdate=27 December 2015|date=September 2004}}</ref> He has taught at the university and retains an involvement with the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]]. He lived in [[Tottenham]], London, for four years and then rural France for six while he developed his career as a novelist.<ref>Rankin, I. (1998) ''Tooth & Nail''. London: Orion. p. vii.</ref> Before becoming a full-time novelist, he worked as a grape picker, [[swineherd]], taxman, alcohol researcher, hi-fi journalist, college secretary and punk musician in a band called the Dancing Pigs.<ref>[http://www.januarymagazine.com/profiles/ianrankin.html \"Profile: Ian Rankin\"], ''January Magazine''</ref><ref>[http://www.bookslut.com/features/2005_04_005009.php \"Ian Rankin\"], Bookslut, April 2005.</ref><ref name = Sturgis/>\n\n==Career==\nRankin did not set out to be a [[crime writer]]. He thought his first novels, ''[[Knots and Crosses]]'' and ''[[Hide and Seek (Ian Rankin novel)|Hide and Seek]]'', were mainstream books, more in keeping with the Scottish traditions of [[Robert Louis Stevenson]] and even [[Muriel Spark]]. He was disconcerted by their classification as genre fiction. The [[List of Scottish novelists|Scottish novelist]] [[Allan Massie]], who tutored Rankin while Massie was writer-in-residence at the University of Edinburgh, reassured him by saying, \"Do you think [[John Buchan]] ever worried about whether he was writing literature or not?\"<ref name=\"Barnett\">{{cite news|author=Barnett, Laura|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/dec/11/ian-rankin-portrait|newspaper=The Guardian|title=Ian Rankin, Author\u2014Portrait of the Artist|date=11 December 2012|accessdate= 8 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nRankin's [[Inspector Rebus]] novels are set mainly in Edinburgh. They are considered major contributions to the [[tartan noir]] genre. Ten of the novels were adapted as a [[Rebus (TV)|television series]] on ITV, starring [[John Hannah (actor)|John Hannah]] as Rebus in series 1 and 2 and [[Ken Stott]] in that role in series 3\u20135.\n\nIn 2009, Rankin donated the short story \"Fieldwork\" to [[Oxfam]]'s ''[[Ox-Tales]]'' project, four collections of UK stories written by 38 authors. Rankin's story was published in the ''Earth'' collection.<ref name=\"Ox\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/shop/content/books/books_oxtales.html |title=Ox-Tales |publisher=Oxfam.org.uk |date= |access-date=4 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520182004/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/shop/content/books/books_oxtales.html |archive-date=20 May 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n[[File:Ian Rankin signing Dark Entries in Forbidden Planet Edinburgh 06.jpg|thumb|Rankin signing copies of his debut graphic novel, ''Dark Entries'', in the Edinburgh [[Forbidden Planet]] International store in December 2009.]]\n\nIn 2009 Rankin stated on [[Radio Five Live]] that he would start work on a five- or six-issue run on the comic book ''[[Hellblazer]]'', although he may turn the story into a stand-alone [[graphic novel]] instead. The Vertigo Comics panel at [[WonderCon]] 2009 confirmed that the story would be published as a [[graphic novel]], ''[[Dark Entries (comics)|Dark Entries]]'', the second release from the company's [[Vertigo Crime]] imprint.<ref name=\"DarkEntries\">{{cite web |title = WC: Vertigo - Innovative and Provocative |date=1 March 2009 |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=20252 |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsarama.com/comics/030925-Vertigo-Rankin.html |title=Starting Vertigo's Crime Line: Ian Rankin on Dark Entries |publisher=[[Newsarama]] |date=25 March 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Duin |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2009/04/ian_rankin_vs_brian_azzarello.html |title=Ian Rankin vs. Brian Azzarello |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |date=7 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Rankin co-wrote the play ''[[Dark Road (play)|Dark Road]]'' with Mark Thomson, the artistic director of the [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.list.co.uk/article/54887-edinburgh-lyceums-mark-thomson-discusses-dark-road-the-first-play-by-ian-rankin/ | title=Mark Thomson Discusses Dark Road, the First Play by Ian Rankin | publisher=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] | work=list.co.uk | date=17 September 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/liam-rudden-lyceum-aims-for-top-rankin-with-dark-road-1-2915455 | title=Lyceum Aims for Top Rankin with Dark Road | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=1 May 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> The play, which marked Rankin's play-writing debut,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/ian-rankin-turns-his-pen-from-rebus-to-stage-play.20959653 | title=Ian Rankin Turns His Pen from Rebus to Stage Play | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=1 May 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> premiered at the Lyceum Theatre, [[Edinburgh]], in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.stv.tv/east-central/223477-rebus-author-ian-rankin-debuts-first-play-as-part-of-lyceum-new-season/ | title=The Lyceum to Host Ian Rankin's Debut Play as Part of New Season | publisher=[[Scottish Television|STV]] | work=news.stv.tv | date=30 April 2013 | accessdate=19 October 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233201/http://news.stv.tv/east-central/223477-rebus-author-ian-rankin-debuts-first-play-as-part-of-lyceum-new-season/ | archive-date=3 March 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nRankin is a regular contributor to the [[BBC Two]] arts programme ''Newsnight Review''. His 3-part documentary series on the subject of [[evil]] was broadcast on [[Channel 4]] in December 2002. In 2005 he presented a 30-minute documentary on [[BBC Four]] called ''Rankin on the Staircase'', in which he investigated the relationship between real-life cases and crime fiction.  It was loosely based on the [[Michael Peterson (author and convicted criminal)|Michael Peterson]] murder case, as covered in Jean-Xavier Lestrade's documentary series ''Death on the Staircase''. The same year he collaborated with folk musician [[Jackie Leven]] on the album ''Jackie Leven Said''.\n\nIn 2007, Rankin appeared in programmes for BBC Four exploring the origins of his alter-ego character, [[John Rebus]]. Titled \"Ian Rankin's Hidden Edinburgh\" and \"Ian Rankin Investigates Dr Jekyll and Mr Hyde,\" Rankin looks at the origins of the character and the events that led to his creation.\n\nIn the TV show ''[[Anthony Bourdain: No Reservations]]'', he takes a trip through Edinburgh with writer/cook [[Anthony Bourdain]].\n\n== Music ==\nRankin is the singer in the six-piece band Best Picture, formed by journalists Kenny Farquharson (''The Times'') and Euan McColl (''The Scotsman'') in 2017, and featuring [[The Bluebells|Bobby Bluebell]] on guitar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farquharson |first1=Kenny |title=The six dads about to rock salute you |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-six-dads-about-to-rock-salute-you-t3x52wf5j |accessdate=28 July 2018 |newspaper=The Times |date=24 October 2017}}</ref>  They released a single \"Isabelle\" on [[Oriel Records]] in October 2017.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ross |first1=Peter |title=Rebus and roll: Ian Rankin\u2019s new gig as a \u2018dad rock\u2019 singer |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/shortcuts/2017/oct/15/rebus-and-roll-ian-rankin-new-gig-as-a-dad-rock-singer |accessdate=28 July 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 October 2017}}</ref>  They made their live debut at the [[Kendal Calling]] music festival on 28 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Picture - Kendal Calling |url=https://www.kendalcalling.co.uk/artists/best-picture |website=Kendal Calling |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe lives in [[Edinburgh]] with his wife, Miranda (n\u00e9e Harvey), whom he met at university and married in 1986, and their two sons: John Morgan \"Jack\" Harvey-Rankin (born 1992) and Christopher Connor \"Kit\" Harvey-Rankin (born 1994). They lived for a number of years in the [[Merchiston]]/[[Morningside, Edinburgh|Morningside]] area,<ref name=\"Williams-Akoto\">{{cite news |last1=Williams-Akoto |first1=Tessa |title=My Home: Ian Rankin, crime writer |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/property/house-and-home/property/my-home-ian-rankin-crime-writer-317152.html |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=The Independent |date=5 October 2005}}</ref> near the authors [[JK Rowling]], [[Alexander McCall Smith]] and [[Kate Atkinson]],<ref name=\"Mitchell\">{{cite news |last1=Mitchell |first1=Hilary |title=Welcome to the 'Writer's Block' - spotlight on exclusive Edinburgh area after Ian Rankin sells house |url=https://www.edinburghlive.co.uk/news/edinburgh-news/welcome-writers-block-spotlight-exclusive-16257774 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Edinburgh Live |date=10 May 2019}}</ref> before moving to a penthouse flat in the former Royal Infirmary building in Quartermile.<ref name=\"MacDonald\">{{cite news |last1=MacDonald |first1=Stuart |title=Author Ian Rankin cashes in on Edinburgh mansion after \u00a32.1 million sale |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/lifestyle/author-ian-rankin-cashes-edinburgh-mansion-after-ps21-million-sale-546995 |accessdate=29 November 2019 |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=10 May 2019}}</ref> The couple also own a house in [[Cromarty]] in the [[Scottish Highlands]].<ref name=\"Reece\">{{cite news |last1=Reece |first1=Alex |title=My Coast: Ian Rankin |url=https://www.coastmagazine.co.uk/content/my-coast-ian-rankin |accessdate=19 November 2019 |work=Coast Magazine}}</ref> Rankin appears as a character in McCall Smith's 2004 novel, ''[[44 Scotland Street]]''.\n\nIn 2011 [[Scottish book sculptures|a group of ten book sculptures]] were deposited around Edinburgh as gifts to cultural institutions and the people of the city. Many of the sculptures made reference to the work of Rankin, and an eleventh sculpture was a personal gift to him.<ref name=CS>{{cite news|title=Mysterious paper sculptures |url=http://thisiscentralstation.com/featured/mysterious-paper-sculptures/|work=Central Stn|first=Chris|last=Scott|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1988 Elected [[Hawthornden Castle|Hawthornden]] Fellow<ref name=\"bfs\">{{cite news|url=http://www.booksfromscotland.com/Authors/Ian-Rankin|publisher=BooksfromScotland.com |title=Ian Rankin |date=|accessdate= 7 January 2013}}</ref>\n*1991 Chandler-[[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] Award<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*1994 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Short Story Dagger for ''A Deep Hole''<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite news |url=http://literature.britishcouncil.org/ian-rankin |publisher=The British Council |title=Ian Rankin |date= |accessdate=7 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605221310/http://literature.britishcouncil.org/ian-rankin |archive-date=5 June 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*1996 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Short Story Dagger for ''Herbert in Motion'' in ''Perfectly Criminal''<ref name=\"CWA\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/short.html|publisher=Crime Writers Association|title=The CWA Short Story Dagger|date=5 July 2012|access-date=7 January 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119201149/http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/short.html|archive-date=19 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*1997 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Gold Dagger for Fiction for ''Black and Blue''<ref name=\"CWA4\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/gold.html|publisher=Crime Writers Association|title=The CWA Gold Dagger|date=5 July 2012|access-date=8 January 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114091850/http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/gold.html|archive-date=14 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*1997 [[Edgar Award]] for best novel, shortlist, ''Black and Blue''\n*1999 [[University of Abertay Dundee]] honorary doctorate <ref name=\"Dundee\">{{cite web|author=THES Editorial|work=The Times Higher Education Supplement|date=26 November 1999|title=Glittering Prizes|accessdate=7 January 2013|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=148995&sectioncode=26}}</ref>\n*2000 [[University of St Andrews]] honorary doctorate<ref name=\"Andrews\">{{cite news|url=http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/news/archive/2000/title,42233,en.php|publisher=University of St Andrews|title=University honour for award winning author|date=3 February 2000|access-date=7 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923131232/http://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/news/archive/2000/title,42233,en.php|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*2000 Palle Rosencrantz Prize (Denmark)<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*2002 Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] for services to literature\n*2003 [[University of Edinburgh]] honorary doctorate<ref name=\"Edinburgh\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/about/people/honorary-degrees/2002-3|publisher=University of Edinburgh|title=University of Edinburgh Honorary Degrees 2002/03|date=28 August 2003|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901213216/http://www.ed.ac.uk/about/people/honorary-degrees/2002-3|archive-date=1 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*2003 Whodunnit Prize (Finland)<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*2003 [[Festival du Film Policier de Cognac|Grand Prix du Roman Noir]] (France)<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*2004 [[Edgar Award]] for ''Resurrection Men''\n*2005 [[Crime Writers Association|CWA]] Lifetime Achievement Award (Cartier [[Diamond Dagger]])''<ref name=\"CWA2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/cartier.html|publisher=Crime Writers Association|title=The Cartier Diamond Dagger|date=5 July 2012|access-date=7 January 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203195758/http://www.thecwa.co.uk/daggers/cartier.html|archive-date=3 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*2005 [[Open University]] honorary doctorate <ref name=\"OU\">{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.open.ac.uk/students/ceremonies/files/ceremonies/file/Doctor%20of%20the%20University%201973-2011.pdf\n |publisher   = The Open University\n |title       = Doctor of the University 1973-2011\n |access-date  = 9 January 2013\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213042428/http://www.open.ac.uk/students/ceremonies/files/ceremonies/file/Doctor%20of%20the%20University%201973-2011.pdf\n |archive-date = 13 December 2013\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n*2005 [[Grand Prix de Litt\u00e9rature Polici\u00e8re]] (France) for ''Set in Darkness''<ref name=\"BC\"/>''<ref name=\"rayonpolarGuidePrix\">{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.rayonpolar.com/Guides/Prix/Prix_pdf.php Guide des Prix litt\u00e9raires], online ed. ''Le Rayon du Polar''. Synopsis of French prizes rewarding French and international crime literature, with lists of laureates for each Prize. Grand Prix de litt\u00e9rature polici\u00e8re: pp. 18-36.</ref>\n*2005 Deutsche Krimi Prize (Germany), for ''Resurrection Men''<ref name=\"BC\"/>\n*2006 [[University of Hull]] honorary doctorate<ref name=\"Hull\">{{cite news|url=http://www2.hull.ac.uk/old_news_pages/news_archive/2006_news_archive/january/honorary_degrees.aspx?theme=textonly|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130419171459/http://www2.hull.ac.uk/old_news_pages/news_archive/2006_news_archive/january/honorary_degrees.aspx?theme=textonly|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 April 2013|publisher=University of Hull|title=The University of Hull awards Honorary Degrees for Inspirational Achievements|date=27 January 2006|access-date=8 January 2013}}</ref>\n*2007 The Edinburgh Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12456608.Rankin_gives_hand_to_Edinburgh_Award/|title=Rankin gives hand to Edinburgh Award|last=|first=|date=2008-02-19|website=The Herald|language=en|access-date=2017-08-05}}</ref>\n*2008 [[ITV3]] Crime Thriller Award for Author of the Year, for ''Exit Music''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Allen, Katie |title=Rankin and P D James pick up ITV3 awards |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/68347-rankin-and-p-d-james-pick-up-itv3-awards.html |work