ustrated by Tim Truman. Published as part of a CD package, ''Kickback City'', featuring [[Rory Gallagher]] songs fictionalized in the novella and with narration by [[Aidan Quinn]]\n\n'''Opera'''\n* ''Gesualdo'', with [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]] (2008)\n'''Short stories'''\n* \"Summer Rites\" (1984) (published in ''Cencrastus'', No. 18 - actually a section of Rankin's first novel)\n* [http://www.theshortstory.org.uk/stories/index.php4?storyid=9 \"An Afternoon\"] (1984) (published in ''[[Association for Scottish Literary Studies#New Writing Scotland|New Writing Scotland No. 2]]'') (slightly revised version published in ''OxCrimes'', 2014)\n* \"Voyeurism\" (1985) (published in ''New Writing Scotland No. 3'')\n* \"Colony\" (1986) (published in ''New Writing Scotland No. 4'')\n* \"Scarab\" (1986) (published in ''Scottish Short Stories 1986'')\n* \"Territory\" (1987) (published in ''Scottish Short Stories 1987'')\n* \"Remembrance\" (1988) (published in ''Cencrastus'', Spring)\n* \"Playback\" (1990) (Rebus; published in Winter's Crime 22; reprinted in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'', 1992)\n* \"Talk Show\" (1991) (Rebus; published in ''Winter's Crimes'' 23)\n* \"The Dean Curse\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Being Frank\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Concrete Evidence\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Seeing Things\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"A Good Hanging\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Tit for Tat\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Not Provan\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Sunday\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Auld Lang Syne\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"The Gentlemen's Club\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"Monstrous Trumpet\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'')\n* \"In the Frame\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''Winter's Crimes'' 24)\n* \"Trip Trap\" (1992) (Rebus; published in ''1st Culprit'')\n* \"Marked for Death\" (1992) (published in ''Constable New Crimes'' 1)\n* \"Well Shot\" (1993) (Rebus; published in ''2nd Culprit''; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Video, Nasty\" (1993) (published in ''Constable New Crimes 2'')\n* \"Castle Dangerous\" (1993) (Rebus; published in ''[[Ellery Queen's Mystery Magazine]]'', ''EQMM'', October)\n* \"Someone Got to Eddie\" (1994) (published in ''3rd Culprit'')\n* \"Facing the Music\" (1994) (Rebus; published in ''Midwinter Mysteries'' 4)\n* \"A Deep Hole\" (1994) (published in ''London Noir'')\n* \"The Serpent's Back\" (1995) (published in ''Midwinter Mysteries'' 5)\n* \"Adventures in Babysitting\" (1995) (published in ''No Alibi'' and in ''Master's Choice Two'')\n* \"Principles of Accounts\" (1995) (published in ''EQMM'', August)\n* \"Window of Opportunity\" (1995) (Rebus, published in ''EQMM'', December)\n* \"Natural Selection\" (1996) (published in ''Fresh Blood'')\n* \"Herbert in Motion\" (1996) (published in ''Perfectly Criminal'')<ref name=\"CWA\"/>\n* \"The Wider Scheme\" (1996) (published in ''EQMM'', August)\n* \"My Shopping Day\" (1997) (Rebus; published in ''Herbert in Motion & Other Stories'' [limited edition chapbook of 200 copies]; not included in the UK edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'', but included in the U.S. edition)\n* \"No. 79\" (1997) (published in Herbert in Motion & Other Stories)\n* \"Glimmer\" (1998) (published in ''Blue Lightning'')\n* \"Unknown Pleasures\" (1998) (published in ''Mean Time'')\n* \"Detective Novels: The Pact Between Authors and Readers\" (1998) (article; published in ''The Writer'', December)\n* \"[[Death is Not the End]]\" (1998) (novella later expanded into ''Dead Souls'')\n* \"The Missing\" (1999) (published in ''Crime Wave'', March)\n* \"Get Shortie\" (1999) (Rebus; published in ''Crime Wave 2, Deepest Red'', June; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Acid Test\" (1999) (Rebus; published in ''EQMM'', August; not included in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Hanged Man\" (1999) (published in ''Something Wicked'' (UK) and ''EQMM'', September/October)\n* \"The Only True Comedian\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', February)\n* \"Unlucky in Love, Unlucky at Cards\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', March)\n* \"The Confession\" (2000) (published in ''EQMM'', June)\n* \"The Slab Boys\" (2000) (published in ''Scenes of Crime'')\n* \"No Sanity Clause\" (2000) (Rebus; originally titled \"Father Christmas's Revenge, published in ''The Daily Telegraph'', December)\n* \"Tell Me Who to Kill\" (2003) (Rebus; published in ''Mysterious Pleasures'')\n* \"Saint Nicked\" (2003/2004) (published in ''The Radio Times'', 21 December 2003 & 4 January 2004)\n* \"Soft Spot\" (2005) (published in ''Dangerous Women'')\n* \"Showtime\" (2005) (published in ''One City'')\n* \"Not Just another Saturday\" (August 2005) (written for SNIP, a charity organisation; people in attendance of the event were provided with a \"typescript\" of the story)\n* \"Atonement\" (2005) (written for the anthology ''Complete Short Stories'', which combined the contents of ''A Good Hanging & Other Stories'' and ''Beggar's Banquet'', but was far from \"Complete\")\n* \"Sinner: justified\" (2006) (published in ''Superhumanatural'')\n* \"Graduation Day\" (2006) (published in ''Murder in the Rough'')\n* \"Fieldwork\" (2009) (published in ''[[Ox-Tales]]'')<ref name=\"Ox\"/>\n* \"Penalty Clause\" (2010) (Rebus; published in ''Mail on Sunday'', December)\n* \"The Very Last Drop\" (2013) (Rebus; written to read aloud at an Edinburgh charity event to help the work of Royal Blind; published in the US and UK editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Dead and Buried\" (2013) (Rebus; published with ''Saints of the Shadow Bible'')\n* \"In the Nick of Time\" (2014) (Rebus; published in ''Face Off'')\n* \"The Passenger\" (2014) (Rebus; published in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"A Three-Pint Problem\" (2014) (Rebus; published in the UK and US editions of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"Cinders\" (2015) (Rebus; published in the US edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'')\n* \"The Travelling Companion\" (2015) (novella, published by the Mysterious Bookshop, NYC; signed, lettered limited cloth edition of 26 copies and 100 numbered copies; softcover edition of 1,000 copies; published in the UK in 2016 by Head of Zeus Ltd, London)\n* \"Meet & Greet\" (2015) (published in ''The Strand'' XLVI)\n* \"The Kill Fee\" (2015) (published in ''The New Statesman'' December 18, 2015\u2014January 8, 2016)\n* \"Cafferty's Day\" (2016) (Rebus; published with ''Rather be the Devil'')\n* \"Charades\" (2017) (Rebus; published in ''Country Life'' December 13/20)\n\n'''Other'''\n* \"Oxford Bar\" (2007) (Essay published in the anthology ''How I Write: The Secret Lives of Authors'')<ref name=\"isfd\">{{cite web|author=|publisher=[[Internet Speculative Fiction Database]]|date=|title=Publication Listing for ''How I Write:The Secret Lives of Authors''|accessdate=12 January 2013|url=http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?312245}}</ref>\n* \"John Rebus\" (2007) (''Mysterious Profile #8'', a chapbook published by the Mysterious Bookshop in NYC in a signed limited hardcover edition of 100 copies and 1,000 softcover copies; reprinted in the UK edition of ''The Beat Goes On: The Complete Rebus Stories'' as \"Rankin on Rebus\")\n* Ian Rankin interviews Arthur Conan Doyle (2013), published in ''Dead Interviews''<ref>{{cite book |author= Dan Crowe (editor) |coauthors=  |title= Dead Interviews: Living Writers Meet Dead Icons |year= 2013 |publisher= Granta, London |pp= [https://archive.org/details/deadinterviewsli0000unse/page/143 143\u2013153] |quote=  |url= https://archive.org/details/deadinterviewsli0000unse/page/143 |isbn= 978-1-84708-827-7 }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n*Alegre, Sara Martin., [https://archive.is/20130624210411/http://mcfarland.metapress.com/content/a68500688130n975/ \"Aging in F(r)iendship: 'Big Ger' Cafferty and John Rebus\"], in ''Clues: A Journal of Detection'' 29.2 (2011): 73-82.\n*Horsley, Lee, ''The Noir Thriller'' (Houndmills & New York: Palgrave, 2001).\n*Lanchester, John, \"Rebusworld\", in ''London Review of Books'' 22.9 (27 April 2000), pp.&nbsp;18\u201320.\n*[[John Lennard|Lennard, John]], \"Ian Rankin\", in Jay Parini, ed., ''British Writers Supplement X'' (New York & London: Charles Scribner's Sons, 2004), pp.&nbsp;243\u201360\n*MacDonald, Erin E., [https://archive.is/20130624210353/http://mcfarland.metapress.com/content/31vjn9282660450w/ \"Ghosts and Skeletons: Metaphors of Guilty History in Ian Rankin's Rebus Series\"], in ''Clues: A Journal of Detection'' 30.2 (2012): 67-75.\n*Mandel, Ernest, ''Delightful Murder: A Social History of the Crime Story'' (Leichhardt, NSW, & London: Pluto Press, 1984).\n*Marshall, Rodney, ''Blurred Boundaries: Rankin's Rebus'' (Amazon, 2012)\n* Nicol, Christopher, \"Ian Rankin's 'Black & Blue'\", Scotnote No.24 (Glasgow: ASLS Publications, 2008)\n*Ogle, Tina, \"Crime on Screen\", in ''The Observer'' (London), 16 April 2000, Screen p.&nbsp;8.\n*Plain, Gill, ''Ian Rankin\u2019s Black and Blue'' (London & New York: Continuum, 2002)\n*Plain, Gillian, \"Ian Rankin: A Bibliography\", in ''Crime Time'' 28 (2002), pp.&nbsp;16\u201320.\n*Robinson, David, \"Mystery Man: In Search of the real Ian Rankin\", in ''The Scotsman'' 10 March 2001, S2Weekend, pp.&nbsp;1\u20134.\n*Rowland, Susan, \"Gothic Crimes: A Literature of Terror and Horror\", in ''From Agatha Christie to Ruth Rendell'' (Houndmills & New York: Palgrave, 2001), pp.&nbsp;110\u201334.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Ian Rankin}}\n* Ian Rankin {{official website|http://www.ianrankin.net}}\n* {{IMDb name|0710256}}\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/authors/author/0,5917,-163,00.html Guardian Books profile], with links to further articles.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/talesofonecity#p/search/5/2K15Gxy_FvU Ian Rankin at Edinburgh Central Library, Oct 2010] (video interview in several parts)\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/2006/TRAVEL/02/03/edinburgh.qa/ CNN interview with Ian Rankin]\n* [http://www.edrants.com/segundo/ian-rankin-bss-390/ 2011 radio interview] at [[The Bat Segundo Show]] (1 hour)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080517015653/http://www.booksfromscotland.com/Authors/Ian-Rankin/Interview-Exit-Music Two BooksfromScotland.com interviews with Ian Rankin]\n* [http://podcast.radionz.co.nz/ntn/ntn-20130226-1008-feature_guest_-_ian_rankin-048.mp3 Radio Interview on RadioNZ's Nine to Noon Show 26 February 2013]\n\n{{Rebus novels}}\n{{Ian Rankin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rankin, Ian}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cardenden]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Scottish comics writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Edgar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Cartier Diamond Dagger winners]]\n[[Category:Members of the Detection Club]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Beath High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Scottish male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish novelists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Tartan Noir writers]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCriticism:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 73-82 \u2192 73\u201382 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ian_Rankin"}
{"title_page": "Emma Bridgewater", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Emma Bridgewater\n| logo = File:Emma Bridgewater Website Logo.png\n| type = \n| industry = [[Ceramic]]s\n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = 1985 \n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owners = Emma Rice CBE, n\u00e9e Bridgewater, Matthew Rice\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk}} \n}}\n[[File:Happiness 1.JPG|thumb|right|A mug made by the company]]\n'''Emma Bridgewater''' is a British ceramics manufacturing company founded in 1985 which is named after Emma Rice CBE, n\u00e9e Bridgewater. It is run by her and her husband Matthew Rice.<ref>{{cite web. Emma completed an MA in illustration in 2019 at Norwich University of the Arts. She got a 1st.\n |url=http://www.bbchomesandantiques.com/feature/designs-we-love/emma-bridgewater\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130117220626/http://www.bbchomesandantiques.com/feature/designs-we-love/emma-bridgewater\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2013-01-17\n |title=Emma Bridgewater \n |publisher=BBC Homes and Antiques \n |accessdate=2010-10-18 \n |last=Wheater \n |first=Caroline \n}}\n</ref> Noted for their [[polka dot]] design among others, the company \"Emma Bridgewater\" specialises in pottery with [[Motif (textile arts)|motifs]] drawing on techniques stretching back over 200 years. The company is one of the largest [[pottery]] manufacturers based entirely in the UK.  Most of its products are made in its factory in the city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[England]],<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk/About-Emma-Bridgewater/About-the-Company/page/aboutthecompany \n |title=About the Company at Emma Bridgewater \n |publisher=www.emmabridgewater.co.uk \n |accessdate=2010-10-18 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205070046/http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk/about-emma-bridgewater/about-the-company/page/aboutthecompany/ \n |archivedate=5 December 2010 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> while others are produced in Poland.\n[[File:CTB 206 Wardle K345OFM v2 - Flickr - megabus13601 (1).jpg|thumb|Bus with Emma Bridgewater livery]]\nThere are two Emma Bridgewater shops in London as well as an [[outlet store]] located at the company's factory.  The products can be purchased from major UK retailers such as John Lewis and House of Fraser.\n\nIn 2016, the company's namesake was made President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cpre.org.uk/media-centre/latest-news-releases/item/4305-emma-bridgewater-announced-as-new-cpre-president\n |title       = CPRE\n |publisher   = www.cpre.org.uk\n |accessdate  = 2017-08-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170808120442/http://www.cpre.org.uk/media-centre/latest-news-releases/item/4305-emma-bridgewater-announced-as-new-cpre-president\n |archivedate = 8 August 2017\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> She is also a Patron of the [[Heritage Crafts Association]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Bridgewater Pottery Works, Eastwood, Hanley - geograph.org.uk - 344857.jpg|thumb|Bridgewater Pottery Works, Eastwood, [[Hanley]]]]\nThe company was founded by [[Emma Bridgewater (person)|Emma Bridgewater]] in 1985, when she was looking for a birthday present for her mother.  Wanting to buy a cup and [[saucer]] but being unable to find any she liked, Emma created her own. Drawing four shapes, a [[mug]], a bowl, a jug and a dish, samples were created in Stoke-on-Trent.<ref name=teleg>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sponsored/business/businesstruth/5279864/Emma-Bridgewater-The-success-of-a-pottery-design-business.html\n|title=Emma Bridgewater: The success of a pottery design business\n|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]\n|date=5 May 2009\n|accessdate=2010-10-18}}\n</ref> Matthew, Emma's husband, also designs for Emma Bridgewater. He indulges his passion for birdlife in the Birds range.<ref name=\"express.co.uk\">{{cite web|last1=Knight|first1=Kathryn|title=Pottery designer Emma Bridgewater: The woman who inspired my designs|url=https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/467376/Pottery-designer-Emma-Bridgewater-says-mum-is-inspiration-behind-designs|website=Express|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In its first year the company had a turnover of around \u00a330,000. By 2009 this had increased to almost \u00a38 million,<ref name=teleg/> and \u00a311 million in 2010, employing 180 people.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10322646\n|title=Emma Bridgewater\n|publisher=BBC Business News\n|accessdate=2010-10-18\n|date=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nEmma Bridgewater's cream [[earthenware]] pottery designs are also adapted for application onto [[textile]]s, glass, tin, stationery, and [[melamine]].<ref name=\"express.co.uk\"/> Her designs include patterns such as Black Toast, Polka Dot, Union Jack, Starry Skies, Pink Hearts and Figs. During a visit by Prince Andrew, a member of the British Royal Family,  Emma discussed the brand's launch of its biggest ever collection of Royal commemorative ware to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee in 2012.<ref>http://6towns.co.uk/news/2012/02/emma-bridgewater-launches-jubilee-collection#.T13fzIHVyI8</ref> Other Royal products have also been launched including the Emma Bridgewater Coronation range as well as commemorative mugs for the birth of Prince George and Princess Charlotte.<ref>{{cite web|title=Memorabilia for Birth of Royal Baby|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/pa/article-3039601/Memorabilia-birth-royal-baby.html|website=Mail Online}}</ref>\n\n== \"Festival in a Factory\" ==\nFor the last few years, the Emma Bridgewater factory in Stoke on Trent has been the home to the \"[[Festival in a Factory]]\" a 3-day literary festival where a number of authors, politicians, artists and celebrities give public lectures.<ref>Video of the 2019 highlights [https://festivalinafactory.co.uk]</ref> The 2020 Festival, planned for 4-6 June,<ref>The cancelled 2020 programme[https://festivalinafactory.co.uk/festival-programme/]</ref> has been cancelled as a result of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Covid-19 pandemic]].\n\nRecent speakers included: [[Mary Portas]], [[Viv Groskop]] [[Elizabeth Day]], [[Christopher Eccleston]], [[Lauren Child]], [[AN Wilson]], historian\u00a0[[Tom Holland (author)|Tom Holland]], author [[Ben Macintyre]], historian [[Andrew Roberts (historian)| Andrew Roberts]], [[Rachel Reeves]] MP, Greepeace UK\u2019s [[Will McCallum]], biographer [[Jenny Uglow]], the National Trust\u2019s [[Nino Strachey]], the [[V&A]]'s [[Oriole Cullen]] and [[Claire Wilcox]], and novelist [[Deborah Moggach]].<ref> speaker list [https://mailchi.mp/b480e532aeb1/emmas-must-see-lit-fest-highlights-4092085?e=a7a2870b88]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=Toast & marmalade and other stories|year=2014|publisher=Saltyard Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-44473-491-1}}\n*{{cite book|title=Pattern|year=2016|publisher=Saltyard Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-44473-494-2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official|http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk}}\n\n{{Stoke-on-Trent}}\n\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of England]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Staffordshire pottery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Emma Bridgewater\n| logo = File:Emma Bridgewater Website Logo.png\n| type = \n| industry = [[Ceramic]]s\n| fate = \n| predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = -->\n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = 1985 \n| founder = \n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = \n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owners = Emma Rice CBE, n\u00e9e Bridgewater, Matthew Rice\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk}} \n}}\n[[File:Happiness 1.JPG|thumb|right|A mug made by the company]]\n'''Emma Bridgewater''' is a British ceramics manufacturing company founded in 1985 which is named after Emma Rice CBE, n\u00e9e Bridgewater. It is run by her and her husband Matthew Rice.<ref>{{cite web. Emma completed an MA in illustration in 2019 at Norwich University of the Arts. She got a 1st.\n |url=http://www.bbchomesandantiques.com/feature/designs-we-love/emma-bridgewater\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130117220626/http://www.bbchomesandantiques.com/feature/designs-we-love/emma-bridgewater\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=2013-01-17\n |title=Emma Bridgewater \n |publisher=BBC Homes and Antiques \n |accessdate=2010-10-18 \n |last=Wheater \n |first=Caroline \n}}\n</ref> Noted for their [[polka dot]] design among others, the company \"Emma Bridgewater\" specialises in pottery with [[Motif (textile arts)|motifs]] drawing on techniques stretching back over 200 years. The company is one of the largest [[pottery]] manufacturers based entirely in the UK.  Most of its products are made in its factory in the city of [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[England]],<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk/About-Emma-Bridgewater/About-the-Company/page/aboutthecompany \n |title=About the Company at Emma Bridgewater \n |publisher=www.emmabridgewater.co.uk \n |accessdate=2010-10-18 \n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205070046/http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk/about-emma-bridgewater/about-the-company/page/aboutthecompany/ \n |archivedate=5 December 2010 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> while others are produced in Poland.\n[[File:CTB 206 Wardle K345OFM v2 - Flickr - megabus13601 (1).jpg|thumb|Bus with Emma Bridgewater livery]]\nThere are two Emma Bridgewater shops in London as well as an [[outlet store]] located at the company's factory.  The products can be purchased from major UK retailers such as John Lewis and House of Fraser.\n\nIn 2016, the company's namesake was made President of the [[Campaign to Protect Rural England]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.cpre.org.uk/media-centre/latest-news-releases/item/4305-emma-bridgewater-announced-as-new-cpre-president\n |title       = CPRE\n |publisher   = www.cpre.org.uk\n |accessdate  = 2017-08-08\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170808120442/http://www.cpre.org.uk/media-centre/latest-news-releases/item/4305-emma-bridgewater-announced-as-new-cpre-president\n |archivedate = 8 August 2017\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref> She is also a Patron of the [[Heritage Crafts Association]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Bridgewater Pottery Works, Eastwood, Hanley - geograph.org.uk - 344857.jpg|thumb|Bridgewater Pottery Works, Eastwood, [[Hanley]]]]\nThe company was founded by [[Emma Bridgewater (person)|Emma Bridgewater]] in 1985, when she was looking for a birthday present for her mother.  Wanting to buy a cup and [[saucer]] but being unable to find any she liked, Emma created her own. Drawing four shapes, a [[mug]], a bowl, a jug and a dish, samples were created in Stoke-on-Trent.<ref name=teleg>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sponsored/business/businesstruth/5279864/Emma-Bridgewater-The-success-of-a-pottery-design-business.html\n|title=Emma Bridgewater: The success of a pottery design business\n|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]]\n|date=5 May 2009\n|accessdate=2010-10-18}}\n</ref> Matthew, Emma's husband, also designs for Emma Bridgewater. He indulges his passion for birdlife in the Birds range.<ref name=\"express.co.uk\">{{cite web|last1=Knight|first1=Kathryn|title=Pottery designer Emma Bridgewater: The woman who inspired my designs|url=https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/467376/Pottery-designer-Emma-Bridgewater-says-mum-is-inspiration-behind-designs|website=Express|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref> In its first year the company had a turnover of around \u00a330,000. By 2009 this had increased to almost \u00a38 million,<ref name=teleg/> and \u00a311 million in 2010, employing 180 people.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10322646\n|title=Emma Bridgewater\n|publisher=BBC Business News\n|accessdate=2010-10-18\n|date=28 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Products ==\nEmma Bridgewater's cream [[earthenware]] pottery designs are also adapted for application onto [[textile]]s, glass, tin, stationery, and [[melamine]].<ref name=\"express.co.uk\"/> Her designs include patterns such as Black Toast, Polka Dot, Union Jack, Starry Skies, Pink Hearts and Figs. During a visit by Prince Andrew, a member of the British Royal Family,  Emma discussed the brand's launch of its biggest ever collection of Royal commemorative ware to celebrate the Queen's Diamond Jubilee in 2012.<ref>http://6towns.co.uk/news/2012/02/emma-bridgewater-launches-jubilee-collection#.T13fzIHVyI8</ref> Other Royal products have also been launched including the Emma Bridgewater Coronation range as well as commemorative mugs for the birth of Prince George and Princess Charlotte.<ref>{{cite web|title=Memorabilia for Birth of Royal Baby|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/wires/pa/article-3039601/Memorabilia-birth-royal-baby.html|website=Mail Online}}</ref>\n\n== \"Festival in a Factory\" ==\nFor the last few years, the Emma Bridgewater factory in Stoke on Trent has been the home to the \"[[Festival in a Factory]]\" a 3-day literary festival where a number of authors, politicians, artists and celebrities give public lectures.<ref>Video of the 2019 highlights [https://festivalinafactory.co.uk]</ref> The 2020 Festival, planned for 4-6 June,<ref>The cancelled 2020 programme[https://festivalinafactory.co.uk/festival-programme/]</ref> has been cancelled as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Covid-19 pandemic]].\n\nRecent speakers included: [[Mary Portas]], [[Viv Groskop]] [[Elizabeth Day]], [[Christopher Eccleston]], [[Lauren Child]], [[AN Wilson]], historian\u00a0[[Tom Holland (author)|Tom Holland]], author [[Ben Macintyre]], historian [[Andrew Roberts (historian)| Andrew Roberts]], [[Rachel Reeves]] MP, Greepeace UK\u2019s [[Will McCallum]], biographer [[Jenny Uglow]], the National Trust\u2019s [[Nino Strachey]], the [[V&A]]'s [[Oriole Cullen]] and [[Claire Wilcox]], and novelist [[Deborah Moggach]].<ref> speaker list [https://mailchi.mp/b480e532aeb1/emmas-must-see-lit-fest-highlights-4092085?e=a7a2870b88]</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=Toast & marmalade and other stories|year=2014|publisher=Saltyard Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-44473-491-1}}\n*{{cite book|title=Pattern|year=2016|publisher=Saltyard Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-44473-494-2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official|http://www.emmabridgewater.co.uk}}\n\n{{Stoke-on-Trent}}\n\n[[Category:Ceramics manufacturers of England]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Stoke-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Staffordshire pottery]]\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e\"Festival in a Factory\":typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Bridgewater"}
{"title_page": "As Simple as Snow", "text_new": "{{Notability|Books|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name         = As Simple as Snow\n| image        = Gregory Galloway - As Simple As Snow.jpeg\n| caption =\n| author       = Gregory Galloway\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| translator   =\n| cover_artist =\n| genre        = [[Young adult fiction]], Mystery\n| publisher    = Putnam\u2019s\n| release_date = 2005\n| media_type   = Print Hardcover\n| pages        = 320pp\n| isbn         = 978-0-399-15231-3\n| oclc=\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''As Simple As Snow''''' (2005) is a [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] novel by [[Gregory Galloway]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Reich|first=Carol|title=As Simple As Snow|work=[[Kliatt]]|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|accessdate=November 25, 2014|date=November 1, 2005|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-138812110.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924133334/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-138812110.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sparks|first=Nicholas|title=Picks and Pans: Books: As Simple As Snow|work=[[People Magazine]]|accessdate=December 10, 2014|date=May 2, 2005|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20197159,00.html}}</ref> It tells the story of a high-school aged narrator who meets a [[Goth subculture|Gothic]] girl, Anna Cayne. Through postcards, a [[shortwave radio]], various mix-CDs, and other erratic interests, Cayne eventually wins the heart of the narrator. However, a week before [[Valentine's Day]], she goes missing, leaving only a dress on the ice and secret codes to help the narrator and the reader find out where she has gone.\n\n==Overview==\nIn a labyrinth of art, [[magic (paranormal)|magic]], cryptic [[codes]] and young love, the author presents a coming-of-age novel that seems designed to puzzle readers of all ages. Moreover, it is an adolescent's quest to unravel the clues his girlfriend may have left behind after her mysterious disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiction Book Review: As Simple As Snow|work=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|date=February 7, 2005|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-399-15231-3}}</ref>\n\nThe young narrator goes unnamed throughout the novel. He disparages himself initially as embarrassingly bland and inexperienced. His new girlfriend Anastasia (Anna) Cayne is instead presented as a complicated high school goth girl with a penchant for riddles and affectionate mind games. Anna spends much of her time creating [[obituaries]] for every living person in town and introducing the narrator to a wider landscape of art, music and literature. She is unlike anyone the narrator has ever known and soon finds himself enveloped in a world of [[Houdini]] tricks, strange art, covert messages, and ghost stories \u2013 although her past remains an even bigger mystery.<ref>{{cite news|title=Books Reviews: As Simple As Snow|work=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|date=May 20, 2010|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/gregory-galloway/as-simple-as-snow/}}</ref>\n\nBut a week before [[Valentine's Day]], Anna disappears, leaving behind nothing except a trail of mysterious clues and a string of unanswered questions. Determined to find Anna, the narrator turns amateur detective in order to piece together the elements of the preceding months. Soon the fragments of events, conversations, and letters (and new messages that continue to arrive) coalesce into haunting and surprising revelations about friends, family and especially about Anna Cayne. Perhaps these revelations will solve the puzzle of Anna's disappearance, whether her own invention, or something more sinister.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.assimpleassnow.com/ AS SIMPLE AS SNOW] The book's website with videoclips, links, and clues\n* [http://www.aadl.org/taxonomy/term/20?page=5 Teens | Ann Arbor District Library] aadl.org\n* [http://www.ala.org/yalsa/booklistsawards/bookawards/alexawards/annotations/06alex 2006 Alex Award] YALSA, American Library Association\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:As Simple As Snow}}\n[[Category:2005 American novels]]\n[[Category:American young adult novels]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:2005 debut novels]]\n\n\n{{2000s-ya-novel-stub}}\n{{2000s-mystery-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Books|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name         = As Simple as Snow\n| image        = Gregory Galloway - As Simple As Snow.jpeg\n| caption =\n| author       = Gregory Galloway\n| country      = United States\n| language     = English\n| translator   =\n| cover_artist =\n| genre        = [[Young adult fiction]], Mystery\n| publisher    = Putnam\u2019s\n| release_date = 2005\n| media_type   = Print Hardcover\n| pages        = 320pp\n| isbn         = 978-0-399-15231-3\n| oclc=\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =\n}}\n\n'''''As Simple As Snow''''' (2005) is a [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] novel by [[Gregory Galloway]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Reich|first=Carol|title=As Simple As Snow|work=[[Kliatt]]|url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research]]|accessdate=November 25, 2014|date=November 1, 2005|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-138812110.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924133334/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-138812110.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sparks|first=Nicholas|title=Picks and Pans: Books: As Simple As Snow|work=[[People Magazine]]|accessdate=December 10, 2014|date=May 2, 2005|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20197159,00.html}}</ref> It tells the story of a high-school aged narrator who meets a [[Goth subculture|Gothic]] girl, Anna Cayne. Through postcards, a [[shortwave radio]], various mix-CDs, and other erratic interests, Cayne eventually wins the heart of the narrator. However, a week before [[Valentine's Day]], she goes missing, leaving only a dress on the ice and secret codes to help the narrator and the reader find out where she has gone.\n\n==Overview==\nIn a labyrinth of art, [[magic (paranormal)|magic]], cryptic [[codes]] and young love, the author presents a coming-of-age novel that seems designed to puzzle readers of all ages. Moreover, it is an adolescent's quest to unravel the clues his girlfriend may have left behind after her mysterious disappearance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiction Book Review: As Simple As Snow|work=[[Publishers Weekly]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|date=February 7, 2005|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-399-15231-3}}</ref>\n\nThe young narrator goes unnamed throughout the novel. He disparages himself initially as embarrassingly bland and inexperienced. His new girlfriend Anastasia (Anna) Cayne is instead presented as a complicated high school goth girl with a penchant for riddles and affectionate mind games. Anna spends much of her time creating [[obituaries]] for every living person in town and introducing the narrator to a wider landscape of art, music and literature. She is unlike anyone the narrator has ever known and soon finds himself enveloped in a world of [[Houdini]] tricks, strange art, covert messages, and ghost stories-although her past remains an even bigger mystery.<ref>{{cite news|title=Books Reviews: As Simple As Snow|work=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|accessdate=December 19, 2014|date=May 20, 2010|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/gregory-galloway/as-simple-as-snow/}}</ref>\n\nBut a week before [[Valentine's Day]], Anna disappears, leaving behind nothing except a trail of mysterious clues and a string of unanswered questions. Determined to find Anna, the narrator turns amateur detective in order to piece together the elements of the preceding months. Soon the fragments of events, conversations, and letters (and new messages that continue to arrive) coalesce into haunting and surprising revelations about friends, family and especially about Anna Cayne. Perhaps these revelations will solve the puzzle of Anna's disappearance, whether her own invention, or something more sinister.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.assimpleassnow.com/ AS SIMPLE AS SNOW] The book's website with videoclips, links, and clues\n* [http://www.aadl.org/taxonomy/term/20?page=5 Teens | Ann Arbor District Library] aadl.org\n* [http://www.ala.org/yalsa/booklistsawards/bookawards/alexawards/annotations/06alex 2006 Alex Award] YALSA, American Library Association\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:As Simple As Snow}}\n[[Category:2005 American novels]]\n[[Category:American young adult novels]]\n[[Category:American mystery novels]]\n[[Category:2005 debut novels]]\n\n\n{{2000s-ya-novel-stub}}\n{{2000s-mystery-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cyanolinguophile", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOverview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/As_Simple_as_Snow"}
{"title_page": "Northern California Athletic Conference", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n|name = Northern California Athletic Conference\n|short_name = NCAC\n|established = 1925\n|dissolved = 1998<ref name=\"grassroots\">{{cite news |last1=Kroichick |first1=Ron |title=A place where college sports are a grassroots movement |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/A-place-where-college-sports-are-a-grassroots-3229843.php |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=SFGate |date=January 23, 2008}}</ref>\n|logo = Northern California Athletic Conference logo.png\n|logo_size = 150\n|association = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]\n|division = [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]\n|subdivision =\n|members = 12 (total)\n|sports = \n|mens = \n|womens = \n|region = [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]]\n|former_names = Far Western Conference (1925&ndash;1982)\n|hq_city = \n|hq_state = \n|commissioner = \n|since = \n|website = \n|color =\n|font_color =\n|map = \n|map_size = \n}}\nThe '''Northern California Athletic Conference''' ('''NCAC'''), a former [[NCAA Division II]] college athletic association that sponsored [[American football]], was formed in 1925. It disbanded in 1998 after the majority of its member schools were forced to drop football.\n\n==History==\nThe NCAC was founded as the '''Far Western Conference''' ('''FWC''') in 1925 by its charter member schools: [[California State University, Fresno|Fresno State]], [[Saint Mary's College of California|Saint Mary's]], [[University of California, Davis|UC Davis]], [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada]], [[San Jos\u00e9 State University|San Jose State]] and [[University of the Pacific (United States)|Pacific]].<ref name=cfdw>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/conference_champs/champions.php?conid=146|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse|accessdate=January 7, 2010|title=Conference Championships: Northern California Athletic Conference}}</ref>\n\nNevada's departure from the conference in 1940 left the conference with only four members; Chico State, Fresno State, College of the Pacific, and UC Davis.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nevada to Quit Far Western Loop|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=A8xYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lugDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4751,5564426&dq=far-western-conference+san-francisco-state&hl=en|accessdate=5 May 2011|newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard|date=Jan 7, 1940}}</ref> The conference looked to four nominees in Humboldt State, San Francisco State, Santa Barbara State, and California Poly of San Luis Obispo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nevada Quits But List Grid Game With COP|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MEgzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ne4HAAAAIBAJ&pg=6446,2188384&dq=far-western-conference+san-francisco-state&hl=en|accessdate=5 May 2011|newspaper=Lodi News-Sentinel|date=Jan 8, 1940}}</ref>\n\nShortly after [[World War II]], all of these charter members, with the exception of UC Davis, would leave for other conferences, to be replaced by [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]], [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State]], [[California State University, East Bay|Hayward State]], [[Southern Oregon University|Southern Oregon]], [[Sonoma State University|Sonoma State]] and [[California State University, Chico|Chico State]].  During the 1990s, each of the universities associated with the California State system chose to disband their football teams in order to comply with [[Title IX]], with the exception of Humboldt State, which added two women's sports to achieve compliance, and Sacramento State University.<ref name=\"grassroots\"/>\n\n==Members==\n[[File:Far Western Conference logo.png|thumb|right]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Institution\n! Location\n! Founded\n! Nickname\n! Joined\n! Left \n! Current<br>conference\n|-\n! [[California State University, Chico|Chico State]]\n| [[Chico, California|Chico, CA]]\n| 1887\n| [[Chico State Wildcats|Wildcats]]\n| 1927\n| 1996\n| [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|-\n! [[California State University, Fresno|Fresno State]]\n| [[Fresno, California|Fresno, CA]]\n| 1911\n| [[Fresno State Bulldogs|Bulldogs]]\n| 1925\n| 1940\n| [[Mountain West Conference|Mountain West]]\n|-\n! [[California State University, East Bay|Hayward State]]\n| [[Hayward, California|Hayward, CA]]\n| 1956\n| [[Cal State East Bay Pioneers|Pioneers]]\n| 1964\n| 1993\n| [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|-\n! [[Humboldt State University|Humboldt State]]\n| [[Arcata, California|Arcata, CA]]\n| 1913\n| [[Humboldt State Lumberjacks|Lumberjacks]]\n| 1930\n| 1996\n| [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|-\n! [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada]]\n| [[Reno, Nevada|Reno, NV]]\n| 1874\n| [[Nevada Wolf Pack|Wolf Pack]]\n| 1925<br>1954\n| 1939<br>1968\n| [[Mountain West Conference|Mountain West]]\n|-\n! [[University of the Pacific (United States)|Pacific (CA)]]\n| [[Stockton, California|Stockton, CA]]\n| 1911\n| [[Pacific Tigers|Tigers]]\n| 1925\n| 1942\n| [[West Coast Conference|West Coast]]\n|-\n! [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State]]\n| [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento, CA]]\n| 1947\n| [[Sacramento State Hornets|Hornets]]\n| 1954\n| 1984\n| [[Big Sky Conference|Big Sky]]\n|-\n! [[Saint Mary's College of California|Saint Mary's]]\n| [[Moraga, California|Moraga, CA]]\n| 1863\n| [[Saint Mary's Gaels|Gaels]]\n| 1925\n| 1928\n| [[West Coast Conference|West Coast]]\n|-\n! [[San Francisco State University|San Francisco State]]\n| [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco, CA]]\n| 1899\n| [[San Francisco State Gators|Gators]]\n| 1947\n| 1995\n| [[California Collegiate Athletic Association|CCAA]]\n|-\n! [[San Jos\u00e9 State University|San Jose State]]\n| [[San Jose, California|San Jose, CA]]\n| 1857\n| [[San Jose State Spartans|Spartans]]\n| 1929\n| 1934\n| [[Mountain West Conference|Mountain West]]\n|-\n! [[Sonoma State University|Sonoma State]]\n| [[Rohnert Park, Californi