n.de/Canada-Ontario.html| archivedate=20 January 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=2006 Community Profiles: London| url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/Page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3539036&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=london&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=| date=6 December 2010| publisher=Statistics Canada| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101234739/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/92-591/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3539036&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=London&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=| archivedate=1 January 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Canada 2016 Census\n!Population\n!% of Total Population\n|-\n| rowspan=\"11\" |[[Visible minority]] group\n<small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=1039&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=Woodstock&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Visible%20minority&TABID=1|title=Community Profiles from the 2016 Census, Statistics Canada - Census Subdivision|date=December 6, 2010|publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=April 13, 2013}}</ref></small>\n|[[Black Canadians|Black]]\n|11,945\n|2.5%\n|-\n|[[Chinese Canadian|Chinese]]\n|10,750\n|2.2%\n|-\n|[[Arab Canadian|Arab]]\n|13,735\n|2.8%\n|-\n|[[South Asia|South Asian]]\n|12,090\n|2.4%\n|-\n|[[Filipino Canadian|Filipino]]\n|3,730\n|0.7%\n|-\n|[[Korean Canadian|Korean]]\n|3,315\n|0.7%\n|-\n|[[Latin American Canadian|Latin American]]\n|9,395\n|1.9%\n|-\n|[[Southeast Asia|Southeast Asian]]\n|5,030\n|1%\n|-\n|[[Japanese Canadians|Japanese]]\n|700\n|0.1%\n|-\n|Other visible minority\n|1,835\n|0.3%\n|-\n|[[Multiracial|Mixed]] visible minority\n|2,505\n|0.5%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Total visible minority population'''\n|'''78,330'''\n|'''16%'''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal]] group\n<small>Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-558/pages/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo=CSD&Code=59&Table=1&Data=Count&Sex=1&Age=1&StartRec=26&Sort=2&Display=Page&CSDFilter=5000|title=Aboriginal Peoples - Data table|date=October 6, 2010|publisher=2.statcan.ca|accessdate=April 13, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130708191912/http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-558/pages/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo=CSD&Code=59&Table=1&Data=Count&Sex=1&Age=1&StartRec=26&Sort=2&Display=Page&CSDFilter=5000|archive-date=8 July 2013|url-status=live}}</ref></small>\n|[[First Nations]]\n|8,795\n|1.8%\n|-\n|[[M\u00e9tis people (Canada)|M\u00e9tis]]\n|2,850\n|0.5%\n|-\n|[[Inuit]]\n|105\n|~0%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Total Aboriginal population'''\n|'''12,070'''\n|2.4\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[European Canadian]]\n|396,105\n|80.8%\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''''Total population'''''\n|'''''486,500'''''\n|'''''100%'''''\n|}\nThe percentage of the resident population in London of retirement age (65 and over) is 16.6, just under Canada's 16.9. The median age is 39.7 years of age, compared to 41.2 for all of Canada.\n\nAs per the 2016 census, the most common ethnicities in London, Ontario are English (28.4%), Canadian (25.8%), Scottish (20.9%), Irish (19.8%), German (11.6%), French (9.6%), Dutch (6.3%), Italian (5.0%), Polish (4.4%), and British Isles Origins, n.i.e. (3.4%).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3539036&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=London&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=Ethnic%20origin&TABID=1&type=1|title=Census Profile, 2016 Census - London, City [Census subdivision], Ontario and Ontario [Province]|last=Government of Canada|first=Statistics Canada|date=2017-02-08|website=www12.statcan.gc.ca|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2011 census, the majority of Londoners profess a [[Christianity|Christian]] faith, which accounts for 62.8 percent of the population (Roman Catholic: 27.0%, Protestant: 25.0%, other Christian: 9.0%). Other religions include [[Islam]] (4.4%), [[Buddhism]] (0.8%), [[Hinduism]] (0.8%), and [[Judaism]] (0.5%), with 29.9 percent of the population reporting no religious affiliation.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:London Ontario Skyline Panorama.jpg|thumb|600px|Panorama of the London skyline viewed from [[Brescia University College]] at the [[University of Western Ontario]]]]\n\nLondon's economy is dominated by [[medical]] research, [[insurance]], [[manufacturing]]<ref>{{cite journal |title=Economic Analysis of Ontario |journal=Central 1 |date=March 2018 |volume=9 |issue=1 |url=https://www.central1.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/London.pdf |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>, and [[information technology]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}} Much of the [[life sciences]] and [[biotechnology]]-related research is conducted or supported by the University of Western Ontario, which adds about C$1.5 billion to the London economy annually.<ref name=\"service\">{{cite web|url=http://www.servicecanada.gc.ca/eng/on/offices/1208lmb/london.shtml |title=London Labour Market Monitor |date=January 2009 |publisher=Service Canada |accessdate=19 July 2009 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nSince the economic crisis of 2009, which gutted many of London's manufacturing jobs, the city has transitioned to become a technology hub with a focus on the Digital Creative sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ledc.com/digital-creative|title=LEDC - London Economic Development Corporation|website=LEDC - London Economic Development Corporation|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-24|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125045409/http://www.ledc.com/digital-creative|archivedate=25 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> As of 2016, London is home to 300 technology companies that employ 3% of the city's labour force.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ledc.com/digital-creative|title=LEDC \u2013 London Economic Development Corporation|website=LEDC \u2013 London Economic Development Corporation|access-date=2016-10-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018220641/http://www.ledc.com/digital-creative|archivedate=18 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Many of these companies have moved into former factories and industrial spaces in and around the downtown core, and have renovated them as modern offices. For example, [[Info-Tech Research Group]]'s London office is in a hosiery factory, and Arcane Digital moved into a 1930s industrial building in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/2015/12/13/a-throwback-to-the-steam-engine-era-an-old-downtown-industrial-warehouse-is-debuting-anew-for-the-search-engine-era|title=The Cube: London's newest digital hothouse|last=nurun.com|website=The London Free Press|access-date=2016-10-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018223944/http://www.lfpress.com/2015/12/13/a-throwback-to-the-steam-engine-era-an-old-downtown-industrial-warehouse-is-debuting-anew-for-the-search-engine-era|archivedate=18 October 2016|df=dmy-all|date=13 December 2015}}</ref> The Historic London Roundhouse, a steam locomotive repair shop built in 1887, is now home to Royal LePage Triland Realty, rTraction, SmartWebPros.com and more. Its redesign, which opened in 2015, won the 2015 Paul Oberman Award for Adaptive Re-Use from the Architectural Conservancy of Ontario.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://londonroundhouse.com/post/130687606205/lrh-honoured-with-aco-award|title=LRH Honoured with ACO Award|website=The London Roundhouse Project|access-date=2016-10-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018234052/http://londonroundhouse.com/post/130687606205/lrh-honoured-with-aco-award|archivedate=18 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> London is also home to [[Diply]], which is ranked among the top websites on the Internet, video game companies [[Big Viking Games]], [[Big Blue Bubble]] and [[Digital Extremes]], and [[Voices.com]], which provides voiceover artists a platform to advertise and sell their services to those looking for voiceover work. Other local tech companies include HRDownloads, Mobials, Race Roster and Zomaron.\n\nThe largest employer in London is the [[London Health Sciences Centre]], which employs 10,555 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ledc.com/resources/business-directory|title=LEDC \u2013 London Economic Development Corporation|website=LEDC \u2013 London Economic Development Corporation|access-date=2016-10-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161017203848/http://www.ledc.com/resources/business-directory|archivedate=17 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe headquarters of the Canadian division of [[3M]] are in London. The [[London Life Insurance Company]] was founded there,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.londonlife.com/002/Home/CorporateInformation/CompanyOverview/index.htm| title=Corporate Information: Company Overview| year=2006| publisher=London Life| accessdate=19 July 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090418035839/http://www.londonlife.com/002/Home/CorporateInformation/CompanyOverview/index.htm| archivedate=18 April 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> as was [[Imperial Oil]],<ref name=\"oil\">{{cite web| title=Our History| url=http://www.imperialoil.ca/Canada-English/Imports/history/about_who_history.aspx| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140731101619/http://www.imperialoil.ca/Canada-English/Imports/history/about_who_history.aspx| archivedate=31 July 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[GoodLife Fitness]], and both the [[Labatt]] and [[Carling]] breweries. The [[Libro Financial Group]] was founded in London 1951 and is the second largest [[credit union]] in Ontario and employs over 550 people.<ref name=\"libro\">{{cite web| title=Introducing the New Libro Credit Union| url=https://www.libro.ca/Community/About.aspx| publisher=Libro Credit Union| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319165810/https://libro.ca/Community/About.aspx| archivedate=19 March 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Canada Trust]] was also founded in London in 1864.<ref name=\"ct\">{{cite book| title=Canada Trust| url=http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/canada-trust/| first1=Alix| last1=Granger| first2=Eric W.| last2=Daly| work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]| date=7 February 2006| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226182504/http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/canada-trust/| archivedate=26 February 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n[[File:London Life Headquarters.jpg|thumb|London Life headquarters in Downtown London]]\n[[General Dynamics Land Systems]] (GDLS) builds [[armoured personnel carrier]]s in the city.<ref name=Gdynamics>{{cite press release |url=http://www.generaldynamics.com/news/press-releases/detail.cfm?customel_dataPageID_1811=9003 |title=General Dynamics Awarded $5 Million Contract to Perform Engineering Studies in Support of Mobile Gun System |date=22 October 2004 |publisher=General Dynamics Land Systems |accessdate=22 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712153947/http://generaldynamics.com/news/press-releases/detail.cfm?customel_dataPageID_1811=9003 |archivedate=12 July 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> GDLS has a 14-year $15-billion deal to supply light armoured vehicles to [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"Post_union\">{{cite web | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/union-asks-ndp-to-keep-saudi-armoured-vehicles-deal-under-wraps-fearing-significant-job-losses | title=Union asks NDP to keep Saudi armoured vehicles deal 'under wraps,' fearing 'significant' job losses | work=Postmedia Network | date=30 September 2015 | accessdate=30 September 2015 | author=De Bono, Norman | url-status=live | archiveurl=http://webarchive.bac-lac.gc.ca:8080/wayback/20150930132738/http://news.nationalpost.com/news/canada/canadian-politics/union-asks-ndp-to-keep-saudi-armoured-vehicles-deal-under-wraps-fearing-significant-job-losses | archivedate=30 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> There are 2,400 workers at GDLS Canada.<ref name=\"Post_union\" />\n\n[[McCormick & Company|McCormick Canada]], formerly Club House Foods, was founded in 1883 and currently employs more than 600 Londoners.\n\nLondon's fledgling city centre mall was first opened in 1960 as Wellington Square with 400,000 sq. ft. of leasable area, with Eaton's and Woolworths as anchors. From 1986 to 1989, Campeau expanded Wellington Square into Galleria London with 1,000,000 sq. ft. of leasable area and 200 stores including The Bay and Eaton's. However the early 1990s recession, following by the bankruptcy of Eaton's in 1999 and then the departure of The Bay in 2000 resulted in only 20 stores left by 2001. Galleria London then begun seeking non-retail tenants, becoming the home for London's [[London Public Library|central library]] branch, and satellite campuses for both [[Fanshawe College]] and [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]]. The complex was purchased and renamed to Citi Plaza by [[Citigroup]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reurbanist.com/2012/06/the-transformation-of-galleria-london/|title=The Transformation of Galleria London - Reurbanist|website=reurbanist.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402150838/http://reurbanist.com/2012/06/the-transformation-of-galleria-london/|archivedate=2 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Citi Plaza has been redeveloped as a mixed use complex that blends retail, office, businesses, and education providers. Alongside Citi Cards Canada's offices, in November 2016, [[CBC News|CBC]] announced plans to move its expanded operations into the building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/london-ontario-cbc-service-1.3836219|title=Public library the new home for CBC's digital, radio programming in London, Ont.|newspaper=CBC News|access-date=2016-11-22|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122220854/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/london-ontario-cbc-service-1.3836219|archivedate=22 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA portion of the city's population work in factories outside of the city limits, including the [[General Motors]] automotive plant [[CAMI Automotive|CAMI]], and a [[Toyota]] plant in [[Woodstock, Ontario|Woodstock]]. A [[St. Thomas Assembly|Ford plant]] in [[Southwold, Ontario|Talbotville]] became one of the casualties of the [[Automotive industry crisis of 2008\u201310|economic crisis]] in 2011.<ref name=ford>{{cite news| title=Ontario Ford plant closure brings tears| url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/09/16/ontario-ford-plant-closure-brings-tears| last=DeBono| first=Norman| date=16 September 2011| work=[[Toronto Sun]]| agency=[[Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia]]| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913165947/http://www.torontosun.com/2011/09/16/ontario-ford-plant-closure-brings-tears| archivedate=13 September 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref><!--See talk page before adding \"Test Market\" material, but there needs to be an inline ref here-->\n\n11 December 2009, [[Minister of State (Canada)|Minister of State]] [[Gary Goodyear]] announced a new $11-million cargo terminal at the [[London International Airport]].<ref name=freight>{{cite news| url=https://lfpress.com/news/london/2009/12/01/11988566-sun.html| accessdate=22 September 2014| title=London lands freight centre| newspaper=London Free Press| last=Dubinski| first=Kate| date=1 December 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402121317/http://www.lfpress.com/news/london/2009/12/01/11988566-sun.html| archivedate=2 April 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{see also|Media in London, Ontario}}\n\n=== Festivals ===\nThe city is home to many festivals including ''[[Sunfest (London, Ontario)|SunFest]]'', the [[London Fringe Theatre Festival (Ontario)|London Fringe Theatre]] Festival, the [[London Ontario Live Arts Festival]] ''(LOLA)'', the [[Home County Folk Festival]], [[Rock the Park]] London, [[Western Fair]], Pride London,<ref name=\"pride\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pridelondon.ca/|title=Pride London Festival|publisher=Pride London Festival|accessdate=24 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102163026/http://www.pridelondon.ca/|archivedate=2 November 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and others. The London [[The London Rib-Fest|Rib Fest]] is the second largest barbecue rib festival in North America.<ref name=\"ribfest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.festivalsontario.com/|title=Ribfest|publisher=Family Shows Canada|accessdate=24 September 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423190734/http://www.festivalsontario.com/|archivedate=23 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Sunfest (London, Ontario)|SunFest]], a [[world music]] festival, is the second largest in Canada after [[Caribana|Toronto Caribbean Carnival]] ''(Caribana)'' and is among the top 100 summer destinations in North America.<ref name=\"sunfest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sunfest.on.ca/|title=About Sunfest|publisher=Sunfest|accessdate=24 September 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090728221232/http://www.sunfest.on.ca/|archivedate=28 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nLondon has a rich musical history. [[Guy Lombardo]], the internationally acclaimed Big-Band leader, was born in London, as was jazz musician [[Rob McConnell]], country music legend [[Tommy Hunter]], singer-songwriter [[Meaghan Smith]], pop icon [[Justin Bieber]], and DJ duo [[Loud Luxury]]; it is also the adopted home-town of hip-hop artist [[Shad (rapper)|Shad Kabango]], rock-music producer [[Jack Richardson (record producer)|Jack Richardson]], and 1960s folk-funk band [[Motherlode (band)|Motherlode]]. American country-music icon [[Johnny Cash]] proposed to his wife [[June Carter Cash]] onstage at the [[London Gardens]]\u2014site of the famous 26 April 1965, fifteen-minute [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert\u2014during his February 22, 1968 performance in the city (which happened to be the home-town of his manager [[My Father and the Man in Black|Saul Holiff]]). Avant-garde noise-pioneers [[Nihilist Spasm Band|The Nihilist Spasm Band]] formed in downtown London in 1965 (between 1966 and 1972, the group held a Monday night residency at the York Hotel in the city's core, which established it as a popular venue for emerging musicians and artists; now known as [[Call the Office]], the venue served as a hotbed for [[punk rock|punk music]] in the late 1970s and 1980s and continues to host college rock bands and weekly alternative-music nights). In 2003, [[CHRW-FM]] developed [[The London Music Archives]], an online music database that chronicled every album recorded in London between 1966 and 2006,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chrwradio.com/lma/|title=94.9 CHRW \u2013 London Music Archive|website=chrwradio.com|access-date=2016-10-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130235352/http://www.chrwradio.com/lma/|archivedate=30 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and in 2019 [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|the CBC]] released a documentary entitled \"London Calling\" which outlined \"The Secret Musical History of London Ontario\" (including its importance for the massively popular [[electronic music|electronic-music]] duo [[Richie Hawtin]] and [[John Acquaviva]]). London also had (and still has, in an unofficial capacity) a professional symphony orchestra -- [[Orchestra London Canada|Orchestra London]]\u2014which was founded in 1937; although the organization filed for bankruptcy in 2015, members of the orchestra continue to play self-produced concerts under the moniker  [https://www.londonsymphonia.ca/ London Symphonia]. In addition, the city is home to the [http://www.lco-on.ca/eng/ London Community Orchestra], the London Youth Symphony, and the [[Amabile Choirs of London, Canada]]. The [[Juno Awards of 2019]] were hosted in London in March 2019, hosted by singer-songwriter [[Sarah McLachlan]].\n\n=== Art ===\nLondon artists [[Jack Chambers (artist)|Jack Chambers]] and [[Greg Curnoe]] co-founded The Forest City Gallery in 1973 and the [[Canadian Artists' Representation]] society  in 1968.  [[Museum London]], the city's central Art Gallery, was established in 1940 (initially operated from the [[London Public Library]], until 1980, when renowned Canadian architect [[Raymond Moriyama]] was commissioned to design its current home at the forks of the [[Thames River (Ontario)|Thames River]]).  London is also home to the [[Museum of Ontario Archaeology]], owned and operated by [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]]; it is Canada's only ongoing excavation and partial reconstruction of a prehistoric village\u2014in this case, a [[Neutral Nation]] village ([[Lawson Site]]).<ref name=\"archaeology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uwo.ca/museum/|title=Museum of Ontario Archaeology|publisher=University of Western Ontario|accessdate=25 September 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714203804/http://www.uwo.ca/museum/|archivedate=14 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[The Royal Canadian Regiment Museum]] is a military museum at [[Wolseley Barracks]] (a Canadian former Forces Base in the city's Carling neighbourhood). The [[Secrets of Radar Museum]] was opened at Parkwood Hospital in 2003, and tells the story of the more than 6,000 Canadian [[World War II]] veterans who were recruited into a top-secret project during [[World War II]] involving [[radar]]. The [[London Regional Children's Museum]] in South London provides hands-on learning experiences for children and was one of the first children's museums established in Canada. The [[Canadian Medical Hall of Fame]] has its headquarters in downtown London and features a medical history museum.\n[[File:Museum London.jpg|thumb|Museum London is at the Forks of the Thames River.]]\n[[Eldon House]] is the former residence of the prominent Harris Family and oldest surviving such building in London. The entire property was donated to the city of London in 1959 and is now a [[heritage site]]. An Ontario Historical Plaque was erected by the province to commemorate The Eldon House's role in Ontario's heritage.<ref name=\"eldon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques_MNO/Plaque_Middlesex13.html|title=Eldon House Historical Plaque|year=2005|publisher=Archives of Ontario|accessdate=24 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516055329/http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques_MNO/Plaque_Middlesex13.html|archivedate=16 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Banting House National Historic Site of Canada is the house where [[Sir Frederick Banting]] thought of the idea that led to the discovery of [[insulin]]. Banting lived and practiced in London for ten months, from July 1920 to May 1921. London is also the site of the Flame of Hope, which is intended to burn until a cure for [[diabetes]] is discovered.<ref name=\"banting\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diabetes.ca/about-us/who/banting-house/banting-square/|title=Sir Frederick G. Banting Square|publisher=Canadian Diabetes Association|accessdate=25 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408072126/http://www.diabetes.ca/about-us/who/banting-house/banting-square/|archivedate=8 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to [[Museum London]] and The Forest City Gallery, London is also home to a number of other galleries and artspaces, including the McIntosh Gallery at [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]], the London ARTS Project, and various smaller galleries such as the Thielsen Gallery, the Westland Gallery, the Michael Gibson Gallery, the Jonathon Bancroft-Snell Gallery, The Art Exchange, the DNA ArtSpace, the VibraFusionLab, and others. London also hosts an annual [[Nuit Blanche]] every June.\n\n=== Theatre ===\n[[File:710 Dundas Palace Theatre.jpg|thumb|The Palace Theatre is in Old East Village, east of downtown.]]\nLondon is home to the [[Grand Theatre, Ontario|Grand Theatre]], a professional [[proscenium arch]] theatre in Central London. The building underwent renovations in 1975 to restore the stage's proscenium arch and to add a secondary performance space. The architectural firm responsible for the redesign was awarded a [[Governor General's Awards|Governor General's award]] in 1978 for their work on the venue. In addition to professional productions, the Grand Theatre also hosts the High School Project, a program unique to North America that provides high school students an opportunity to work with professional [[Theatre director|directors]], [[choreographer]]s, [[musical director]]s, and [[stage managers]]. The Palace Theatre, in Old East Village, originally opened as a silent movie theatre in 1929 and was converted to a live theatre venue in 1991.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.palacetheatre.ca/history-of-the-palace/|title=History of The Palace|website=The Palace Theatre|access-date=2016-10-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019160605/http://www.palacetheatre.ca/history-of-the-palace/|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is currently the home of the [[London Community Players]], and as of 2016 is undergoing extensive historical restoration. The Original Kids Theatre Company, a nonprofit charitable youth organisation, currently puts on productions at the Spriet Family Theatre in the Covent Garden Market.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://originalkids.ca/our-history.html|title=Our History|website=Original Kids Theatre Company|access-date=2016-10-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019143637/http://originalkids.ca/our-history.html|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nLondon serves as a core setting in [[Southern Ontario Gothic]] literature, most notably in the works of [[James Reaney]]. In 1995, rock-star [[David Bowie]] based his \"Nonlinear Gothic Drama Hypercycle\" ''[[Outside (David Bowie album)|Outside]]'' in London, subtly and suggestively reaffirming its status as a core setting of Southern Ontario Gothic works. Author [[David Southwell]] (perhaps in reference to David Bowie's 1995 [[Southern Ontario Gothic]] hypercycle and/or Bowie's character in [[David Lynch]]'s ''[[Twin Peaks]]'') likened London Ontario to the setting of Lynch's weird and wonderful TV-show ''[[Twin Peaks]]'' and/or a woodsy \"Mirror London\" akin to [[China Mi\u00e9ville]]'s underworld-wonderworld ''[[Un Lun Dun]]''. The pioneering psychologist [[Richard Maurice Bucke]], author of ''[[Cosmic Consciousness|Cosmic Consciousness: A Study in the Evolution of the Human Mind]]'' and [[Walt Whitman]]'s literary executor, lived and worked in London, where he was often visited by Whitman<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/collectionsp-bin/colldisp/l=0/c=98 |title=Search - Directory of Special Collections of Research Value in Canadian Libraries |access-date=7 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307053433/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/collectionsp-bin/colldisp/l=0/c=98 |archive-date=7 March 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> (the [[Richard Maurice Bucke|Maurice Bucke Archive]] are part of the Special Collections in [[D. B. Weldon Library|The Weldon Library]] of [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]]). Modern writers from this city include fantasy-fiction authors [[R. Scott Bakker]] and [[Kelley Armstrong]], [[Man Booker Prize]] winner [[Eleanor Catton]], [[Scotiabank Giller Prize]] winner [[Bonnie Burnard]] and distinguished nominee [[Joan Barfoot]]. [[Emma Donoghue]], whose 2010 novel, [[Room (novel)|''Room'']], was adapted into a [[Room (2015 film)|2015 Academy Award-winning film]] of the same name, also lives in London. WordFest is an annual literary and creative arts festival that takes place each November.\n\n=== Livability ===\n[[File:Thames River Springbank Park.jpg|thumb|Springbank Park, located along the Thames River, is London's largest park.]]\n\nThe city's cost of living is low compared to other southern Ontario cities. According to the London St. Thomas Association of Realtors, the average price of a home in the London and [[St. Thomas, Ontario|St. Thomas]] area in 2016 is $274,383, which is substantially lower than the national average of $467,082. It is also well below the average home prices of nearby cities including [[Toronto]] ($736,670), [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] ($510,204), and [[Kitchener-Waterloo]] ($364,290).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lstar.ca/news/best-september-ever-0|title=Best September EVER {{!}} London St. Thomas Association of Realtors|website=www.lstar.ca|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019153820/http://www.lstar.ca/news/best-september-ever-0|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 2015 average rental rate for a one-bedroom apartment is $781.\n\nLondon has nine major parks and gardens throughout the city, many of which run along the [[Thames River (Ontario)|Thames River]] and are interconnected by a series of pedestrian and bike paths, known as the Thames Valley Parkway.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london.ca/residents/Parks/Explore-Parks/Pages/Major-Parks-Gardens.aspx|title=Major Parks and Gardens|website=www.london.ca|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019153259/https://www.london.ca/residents/Parks/Explore-Parks/Pages/Major-Parks-Gardens.aspx|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This path system is 40&nbsp;km (25&nbsp;mi) in length, and connects to an additional 150&nbsp;km (93&nbsp;mi) of bike and hiking trails throughout the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london.ca/residents/Parks/Explore-Parks/Pages/Thames-Valley-Parkway.aspx|title=Thames Valley Parkway|website=www.london.ca|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019151155/https://www.london.ca/residents/Parks/Explore-Parks/Pages/Thames-Valley-Parkway.aspx|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The city's largest park, [[Springbank Park]], is 140-hectare (300 acre) and contains 30&nbsp;km (19&nbsp;mi) of trails. It is also home to Storybook Gardens, a family attraction open year-round.\n\n== Sports ==\n[[File:London vs Hamilton.jpg|thumb|London Majors, Spring 2008]]\n[[File:John Labatt Centre - Talbot Inn corner.jpg|thumb|Budweiser Gardens is home to the London Knights and the London Lightning.]]\nLondon is currently the home of the [[London Knights]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]], who play at the [[Budweiser Gardens]]. The Knights are 2004\u20132005 and 2015\u20132016 OHL and [[Memorial Cup]] Champions. During the summer months, the [[London Majors]] of the [[Intercounty Baseball League]] play at [[Labatt Park]]. [[London City (soccer club)|London City]] of the [[Canadian Soccer League (current)|Canadian Soccer League]], is the highest level of soccer in London. The club was founded in 1973; it is the oldest active professional soccer franchise in North America.<ref name=CSL>{{cite web| url=http://www.canadiansoccerleague.ca/news_archive.php?news_id=76064| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201111250/http://www.canadiansoccerleague.ca/news_archive.php?news_id=76064| archivedate=1 December 2008|title=Canadian Soccer League| year=2007| accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> The squad plays at [[Cove Road Stadium]] at the German Canadian Club. Other sports teams include the London Silver Dolphins Swim Team, the Forest City Volleyball Club, London Cricket Club, the London St. George's Rugby Club, the London Aquatics Club, the London Rhythmic Gymnastics Club, the London Rowing Club, London City Soccer Club and [[Forest City London]].\n[[File:Labatt Memorial park.JPG|thumb|Labatt Memorial Park is the oldest operating baseball diamond in North America.]]\nFootball teams include the London Beefeaters (Ontario Football Conference).\n\nLondon's basketball team, the [[London Lightning]] plays at [[Budweiser Gardens]] as members of the [[National Basketball League of Canada]]. Finishing their inaugural regular season at 28\u20138, the Lightning would go on to win the [[2011-12 NBL Canada season|2011\u201312]] NBL Canada championship, defeating the [[Halifax Rainmen]] in the finals three games to two.\n\nThere are also a number of former sports teams that have moved or folded. London's four former baseball teams are the [[London Monarchs (baseball)|London Monarchs]] ([[Canadian Baseball League]]), the [[London Werewolves]] ([[Frontier League]]), the [[London Tecumsehs]] ([[International Association (baseball)|International Association]]) and the [[London Tigers]] (AA [[Eastern League (U.S. baseball)|Eastern League]]). Other former sports teams include the London Lasers ([[Canadian Soccer League (1987\u20131992)|Canadian Soccer League]])\n\nIn March 2013, London hosted the [[2013 World Figure Skating Championships]].\n\nThe University of Western Ontario's teams play under the name ''Mustangs''. The university's football team plays at [[TD Waterhouse Stadium]].<ref name=UWOfacilities>{{cite web| url=http://www.westernmustangs.ca/sports/2009/7/6/GEN_0706090232.aspx?tab=facilities| title=Facilities| year=2009| publisher=University of Western Ontario| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926082245/http://www.westernmustangs.ca/sports/2009/7/6/GEN_0706090232.aspx?tab=facilities| archivedate=26 September 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Western's Rowing Team rows out of a boathouse at Fanshawe Lake. Fanshawe College teams play under the name ''Falcons''. The Women's Cross Country team has won 3 consecutive [[Canadian Collegiate Athletic Association]] (CCAA) National Championships.<ref name=lethbridge>{{cite web| url=http://www.ccaa.ca/lethbridge-runners-cross-the-finish-line-first-at-the-2008-ccaa-cross-country-running-open-p185913| title=Lethbridge Runners cross the finish line first at the 2008 CCAA Cross Country Running Open| date=June 2009| publisher=CCAA| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402151243/http://www.ccaa.ca/lethbridge-runners-cross-the-finish-line-first-at-the-2008-ccaa-cross-country-running-open-p185913| archivedate=2 April 2015| df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, the program cemented itself as the first CCAA program to win both Men's and Women's National team titles, as well as CCAA Coach of the Year.<ref name=top2010>{{cite web| url=http://www.ccaa.ca/web/index.php/en/cc-news-archive/601-alberta-runners-top-2010-ccaa-cross-country-running-nationals| title=Alberta Runners Top 2010 CCAA Cross Country Running Nationals| publisher=CCAA| accessdate=5 April 2012| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120308155931/http://www.ccaa.ca/web/index.php/en/cc-news-archive/601-alberta-runners-top-2010-ccaa-cross-country-running-nationals| archivedate=8 March 2012| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Western Fair Raceway, about 85 acres [[harness racing]] track and simulcast centre, operates year-round.<ref name=westernfair>{{cite web| url=http://www.westernfair.com/race/home.html| title=Western Fair Raceway| year=2006| publisher=Western Fair Entertainment Centre| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902040551/http://www.westernfair.com/race/home.html| archivedate=2 September 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The grounds include a coin slot [[casino]], a former [[IMAX]] theatre, and Sports and Agri-complex. [[Labatt Memorial Park]] the world's oldest continuously used baseball grounds<ref>{{cite news| title=April Baseball at Historic Labatt Park| url=https://lfpress.com/ur/story/870615| last=McLarty| first=Butch| date=1 April 2014| work=London Free Press| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042955/http://www.lfpress.com/ur/story/870615| archivedate=8 August 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.ca/Sports_and_Recreation/PDFs/2008Newsletter.pdf |title=Parks and Recreation Newsletter |date=June 2008 |publisher=City of London |accessdate=27 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603234324/http://www.london.ca/Sports_and_Recreation/PDFs/2008Newsletter.pdf |archivedate=3 June 2011 }}</ref> was established as Tecumseh Park in 1877; it was renamed in 1937, because the London field has been flooded and rebuilt twice (1883 and 1937), including a re-orientation of the bases (after the 1883 flood). The [[Forest City Velodrome]], at the former [[London Ice House]], is the only indoor cycling track in Ontario and the third to be built in North America, opened in 2005.<ref name=attractions>{{cite web| url=http://www.london.ca/d.aspx?s=/Attractions/default.htm| title=Attractions| year=2009| publisher=City of London| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125095911/http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=%2FAttractions%2Fdefault.htm| archivedate=25 November 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> London is also home to World Seikido, the governing body of a martial art called Seikido which was developed in London in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldseikido.com/html/about/founders.html|title=World Seikido - Founders|website=worldseikido.com|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Current franchises ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+ Active sports teams in London <!-- sorted by date established -->\n|-\n! Club\n! League\n! Sport\n! Venue\n! Established\n! Championships\n|-\n! [[London Knights]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| [[Budweiser Gardens]]\n| 1965\n| 4\n|-\n! [[London Nationals]]\n| [[GOJHL]]\n| [[Ice hockey]]\n| [[Western Fair District]]\n| 1950\n| 7\n|-\n! [[London Lightning]]\n| [[National Basketball League of Canada|NBL Canada]]\n| [[Basketball]]\n| [[Budweiser Gardens]]\n| 2011\n| 3\n|-\n! [[London Majors]]\n| [[Intercounty Baseball League|IBL]]\n| [[Baseball]]\n| [[Labatt Memorial Park]]\n| 1925\n| 9\n|-\n! [[London St. George's RFC]]\n| [[Ontario Rugby Union|ORU]] (Marshall Premiership)\n| [[Rugby Union]]\n| [[London St. George's Club]]\n| 1959\n| 0\n|-\n! [[Forest City London]]\n| [[League1 Ontario]]\n| [[Soccer]]\n| [[TD Waterhouse Stadium]]\n| 2009\n| 1\n|-\n! [[London Beefeaters]]\n| [[Canadian Junior Football League|CJFL]]\n| [[Canadian Football]]\n| TD Waterhouse Stadium\n| 1975\n| 1\n|-\n! [[London Blue Devils]]\n| [[Ontario Junior B Lacrosse League]]\n| [[Lacrosse]]\n| [[Earl Nichols Recreation Centre]]\n| 2003\n| 0\n|}\n\n== Government and law ==\n{{See also|London City Council|List of mayors of London, Ontario}}\n[[File:Wellington Road Downtown London.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Wellington Street in downtown London, viewed atop London City Hall]]\nLondon's [[Local government|municipal government]] is divided among fourteen [[councillor]]s (one representing each of London's fourteen [[ward (politics)|wards]]) and the [[mayor]]. [[Matt Brown (Canadian politician)|Matt Brown]] was elected mayor in the [[London, Ontario municipal election, 2014|2014 municipal election]], officially taking office {{as of|2014|12|1|alt=on 1 December 2014}}.<ref>[http://london.ctvnews.ca/matt-brown-elected-as-new-mayor-of-london-1.2074064 \"Matt Brown elected as new mayor of London\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030051413/http://london.ctvnews.ca/matt-brown-elected-as-new-mayor-of-london-1.2074064 |date=30 October 2014 }}. [[CFPL-DT|CTV London]], 27 October 2014.</ref> Prior to Brown's election, London's [[List of mayors of London, Ontario|most recent elected mayor]] was [[Joe Fontana]]; following Fontana's resignation on 19 June 2014, city councillor Joe Swan served as [[acting mayor]]<ref name=resign>{{cite news| url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/06/19/joe-fontana-officially-resigns-as-mayor-of-london| title=Joe Fontana officially resigns as mayor of London| work=Toronto Sun| date=19 June 2014| last=Maloney| first=Patrick| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027211311/http://www.torontosun.com/2014/06/19/joe-fontana-officially-resigns-as-mayor-of-london| archivedate=27 October 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> until councillor Joni Baechler was selected as interim mayor 24 June.<ref name=replace>{{cite news| title=London, Ont. names new mayor to replace Fontana| url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/06/24/london-ont-names-new-mayor-to-replace-fontana| work=Toronto Sun| date=24 June 2014| agency=Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia| last=Maloney| first=Patrick| accessdate=22 September 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027230811/http://www.torontosun.com/2014/06/24/london-ont-names-new-mayor-to-replace-fontana| archivedate=27 October 2014| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Until the elections in 2010, there was a [[Board of Control (municipal government)|Board of Control]], consisting of four controllers and the mayor, all elected citywide.<ref name=\"council\">{{cite web| url=http://www.london.ca/d.aspx?s=/City_Council/default.htm| title=Your December 2006 \u2013 November 2010 Council| year=2006| publisher=City of London| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125123613/http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=%2FCity_Council%2Fdefault.htm| archivedate=25 November 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough London has many ties to [[Middlesex County, Ontario|Middlesex County]], it is a totally separate entity; the two have no jurisdictional overlap. The exception is the Middlesex County courthouse and former jail, as the judiciary is administered directly by the province.<ref name=middlesex>{{cite web| url=http://www.county.middlesex.on.ca/CountyInformation/About_Middlesex.asp| title=Middlesex County Information| publisher=Middlesex County| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090905035823/http://www.county.middlesex.on.ca/CountyInformation/About_Middlesex.asp| archivedate=5 September 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLondon was the first city in Canada (in May 2017) to decide to move a [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked choice ballot]] for municipal elections starting in 2018. Voters mark their ballots in order of preference, ranking their top three favourite candidates. An individual must reach 50 per cent of the total to be declared elected; in each round of counting where a candidate has not yet reached that target, the person with the fewest votes is dropped from the ballot and their second or third choice preferences reallocated to the remaining candidates, with this process repeating until a candidate has reached 50 per cent.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/london-ranked-ballot-1.4095014 \"London, Ont., votes to become 1st Canadian city to use ranked ballots\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503090057/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/london-ranked-ballot-1.4095014 |date=3 May 2017 }}. [[CBC News]] Windsor, May 2, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 2001, the City of London first published their Facilities Accessibility Design Standards (FADS) which was one of the first North American municipal [[accessibility]] requirements to include [[Universal Design]]. It has since been adopted by over 50 municipalities in [[Canada]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.london.ca/city-hall/accessibility/Pages/Facilities-Accessibility-Design-Standards.aspx| title=Facilities Accessibility Design Standards (FADS)| year=2016| publisher=City of London Ontario| accessdate=20 August 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621174137/http://www.london.ca/city-hall/accessibility/Pages/Facilities-Accessibility-Design-Standards.aspx| archivedate=21 June 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== City councilors ===\nIn addition to mayor Ed Holder, the following were elected in the [[London, Ontario municipal election, 2018|2018 municipal election]] for the 2018\u20132022 term:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.london.ca/city-hall/elections/Results/Documents/2018-Election-Results.pdf |title=City of London Official Municipal 2018 Election Results |access-date=23 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123121737/http://www.london.ca/city-hall/elections/Results/Documents/2018-Election-Results.pdf |archive-date=23 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  cellpadding=2 cellspacing=2 width=50%\n!style=\"background:#cccccc;\"| ''Councillor''\n!style=\"background:#cccccc;\"| ''Office''\n!style=\"background:#cccccc;\"| ''Communities''\n|-\n\n|-\n| Michael van Holst || Ward 1 || Chelsea Green, Fairmont, Hamilton Road, River Run, The Gore, Glen Cairn\n \n|-\n| Shawn Lewis || Ward 2 || Argyle, Crumlin, Pottersburg, Nelson Park, Trafalgar Heights\n|-\n| Mo Mohamed Salih || Ward 3 || Airport, Fanshawe, Huron Heights, The Grove\n|-\n| Jesse Helmer || Ward 4 || East London\n|-\n| Maureen Cassidy || Ward 5 || Stoneybrook, Northdale, Northerest, Uplands\n|-\n| Phil Squire || Ward 6 || Broughdale, University Heights, Orchard Park, Sherwood Forest\n|-\n| Josh Morgan || Ward 7 || White Hills, Medway Heights, Masonville, Hyde Park\n|-\n| Steve Lehman || Ward 8 || Oakridge Park, Oakridge Acres, \n|-\n| Anna Hopkins || Ward 9 || Byron, Lambeth, Woodhull, River Bend, Sharon Creek, Southwinds, Talbot\n|-\n| Paul Van Meerbergen || Ward 10 || Westmount, Rosecliffe Estates\n|- \n| Stephen Turner || Ward 11 || Cleardale, Southcrest Estates, Berkshire Village, Kensal Park, Manor Park\n|-\n| Elizabeth Peloza || Ward 12 || Glendale, Southdale, Lockwood Park, White Oak\n|- \n| Arielle Kayabaga|| Ward 13 || Downtown London, Midtown, Blackfriars, Piccadilly/Adelaide, SoHo, Kensington, Woodfield, Oxford Park\n|-\n| Steve Hillier || Ward 14 || Glen Cairn Woods, Pond Mills, Wilton Grove, Glanworth\n|}\n\n=== Provincial ridings ===\nThe city includes four provincial ridings. In the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario|provincial government]], London is represented by [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democrats]] [[Terence Kernaghan]] ([[London North Centre (provincial electoral district)|London North Centre]]), [[Teresa Armstrong]] ([[London\u2014Fanshawe (provincial electoral district)|London\u2014Fanshawe]]) and [[Peggy Sattler]] ([[London West (provincial electoral district)|London West]]), and [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Progressive Conservative]] [[Jeff Yurek]] ([[Elgin\u2014Middlesex\u2014London (provincial electoral district)|Elgin\u2014Middlesex\u2014London]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/members/members_current.do?locale=en&ord=Riding&dir=ASC&list_type=all_mpps| title=Current MPPs| publisher=Legislative Assembly of Ontario| accessdate=26 October 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193611/http://www.ontla.on.ca/web/members/members_current.do?locale=en&ord=Riding&dir=ASC&list_type=all_mpps| archivedate=29 October 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal ridings ===\nThe London and surrounding area includes four federal ridings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/canada-election-2015-london-west-north-centre-fanshawe-elgin-middlesex-1.3278673|title=London ridings: Canada Election 2015 results|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108013201/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/canada-election-2015-london-west-north-centre-fanshawe-elgin-middlesex-1.3278673|archivedate=8 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the [[House of Commons of Canada|federal government]], London is represented by Conservative [[Karen Vecchio]] ([[Elgin\u2014Middlesex\u2014London]]), Liberals [[Peter Fragiskatos]] ([[London North Centre]]) and [[Kate Young (politician)|Kate Young]] (London West), and NDP [[Irene Mathyssen]] ([[London\u2014Fanshawe]]).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://webinfo.parl.gc.ca/MembersOfParliament/MainMPsCompleteList.aspx?TimePeriod=Current&Language=E| title=Members of Parliament| publisher=Parliament of Canada| accessdate=7 June 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424171818/http://webinfo.parl.gc.ca/MembersOfParliament/MainMPsCompleteList.aspx?Language=E&TimePeriod=Current| archivedate=24 April 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Crime ===\nStatistics from police indicate that total overall crimes in London have held steady between 2010 and 2016, at roughly 24,000 to 27,000 incidents per year.<ref>[https://www.londonpolice.ca/en/about/Crime-Statistics.aspx Crime Statistics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815020719/http://www.londonpolice.ca/en/about/Crime-Statistics.aspx |date=15 August 2016 }} from LondonPolice.ca, accessed 10 Aug 2018</ref> The majority of incidents are property crimes, with violent crimes dropping markedly (up to about 20%) between 2012-2014 but rising again in 2015\u20132016. In July 2018, Police Deputy Chief Steve Williams was quoted as saying many crimes go unreported to police.<ref>CBC News, [https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/london-crime-severity-rate-stats-canada-1.4759610 London crime severity rate sees an increase, report says] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816043131/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/london/london-crime-severity-rate-stats-canada-1.4759610 |date=16 August 2018 }},  Jul 24, 2018, accessed 10 Aug 2018</ref>\n\nResearch by [[Michael Andrew Arntfield]], a police officer turned criminology professor, has determined that on a per-capita basis, London Ontario had more active [[serial killers]] than any locale in the world from 1959 to 1984.<ref>Michael Arntfield (2018). Murder City: The Untold Story of Canada's Serial Killer Capital, 1959-1984. FriesenPress</ref> Arntfield determined there were at least six serial killers active in London during this era, some unidentified, but known killers in London included [[Russell Maurice Johnson]], [[Gerald Thomas Archer]], and Christian Magee.<ref>Jared Lindzon [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/19/serial-killer-london-ontario-canada What turned one city in Canada into the 'serial killer capital' of the world?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510110808/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/19/serial-killer-london-ontario-canada |date=10 May 2017 }}, TheGuardian.com, Aug 19, 2015; accessed 10 Aug 2018</ref>\n\n=== Civic initiatives ===\nThe City of London initiatives in Old East London are helping to create a renewed sense of vigour in the East London Business District. Specific initiatives include the creation of the Old East Heritage Conservation District under Part V of the ''Ontario Heritage Act'', special Building Code policies and Facade Restoration Programs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.oldeastvillage.com/pdf_reports/Re-establishingValue-aPlanfortheOldEastVillage.pdf| title=Re-establishing Value| publisher=Ontario Professional Planners Institute| accessdate=17 July 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106114902/http://www.oldeastvillage.com/pdf_reports/Re-establishingValue-aPlanfortheOldEastVillage.pdf| archivedate=6 January 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLondon is home to heritage properties representing a variety of [[architectural style]]s,<ref name=\"heritage\">{{cite web| url=http://www.london.ca/d.aspx?s=/Heritage/HeritageCitymap.htm| title=Heritage Inventory| publisher=City of London| accessdate=24 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125182835/http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=%2FHeritage%2FHeritageCitymap.htm| archivedate=25 November 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> including [[Queen Anne Style architecture|Queen Anne]], [[Art Deco]], [[Modern movement|Modern]], and [[Brutalist architecture|Brutalist]]\n\nLondoners have become protective of the trees in the city, protesting \"unnecessary\" removal of trees.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.londonkiosk.ca/london-tourism.php| title=London Tourism Information| year=2009| publisher=London Kiosk| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220151300/http://www.londonkiosk.ca/london-tourism.php| archivedate=20 February 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> The City Council and tourist industry have created projects to replant trees throughout the city. As well, they have begun to erect metal trees of various colours in the downtown area, causing some controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazette.uwo.ca/pdf/Gazette-2008-09-30.pdf |title=Metal Tree Planting Continues |last=Haggarty |first=Jaclyn |date=30 September 2008 |newspaper=UWO Gazette |page=1 |accessdate=21 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611181107/https://www.gazette.uwo.ca/pdf/Gazette-2008-09-30.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n{{see also|List of roads in London, Ontario}}\n\n=== Road transportation ===\n[[File:Highway 401 from Wellington Road in London, Looking West Towards Highway 402.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] in London looking towards [[Ontario Highway 402|Highway 402]] from [[Wellington Road (London, Ontario)|Wellington Road]]]]\nLondon is at the junction of [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] that connects the city to Toronto and Windsor, and [[Ontario Highway 402|Highway 402]] to [[Sarnia]].<ref name=\"goodmove\">{{cite web| url=http://goodmovelondon.com/gettingto/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503121435/http://goodmovelondon.com/gettingto/| archivedate=3 May 2008| title=Getting to London| year=2006| publisher=LEDC| accessdate=27 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mto.gov.on.ca/english/news/regional/2000/2000-0001.shtml| title=Ontario government improving Highway 402 between London and Sarnia| year=2009| publisher=Government of Ontario| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630002953/http://www.mto.gov.on.ca/english/news/regional/2000/2000-0001.shtml| archivedate=30 June 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also, [[Ontario Highway 403|Highway 403]], which diverges from the 401 at nearby [[Woodstock, Ontario]], provides ready access to [[Brantford]], [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], the [[Golden Horseshoe]] area, and the [[Niagara Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.thekingshighway.ca/Highway403.htm| title=The King's Highway 403| last=Bevers| first=Cameron| year=2002| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306075339/http://www.thekingshighway.ca/Highway403.htm| archivedate=6 March 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Many smaller two-lane [[highway]]s also pass through or near London, including [[King's Highways in Ontario|Kings Highway]]s [[Ontario Highway 2|2]], [[Ontario Highway 3|3]], [[Ontario Highway 4|4]], [[Ontario Highway 7|7]] and 22. Many of these are \"historical\" names, as provincial downloading in the 1980s and 1990s put responsibility for most provincial highways on municipal governments.<ref name=kingshwy>{{cite web| url=http://www.thekingshighway.ca/Highway24.htm| title=The King's Highway 24| last=Bevers| first=Cameron| year=2002| accessdate=27 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100730074215/http://www.thekingshighway.ca/Highway24.htm| archivedate=30 July 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nevertheless, these roads continue to provide access from London to nearby communities and locations in much of [[Western Ontario]], including [[Goderich, Ontario|Goderich]], [[Port Stanley, Ontario|Port Stanley]] and [[Owen Sound]].\n\n[[File:Veterans Memorial Parkway, London, Ontario.jpg|thumb|right|Intersection along the [[Veterans Memorial Parkway]], an at-grade [[limited-access road|expressway]]]]\nSince the 1970s, London has improved urban road alignments that eliminated \"jogs\" in established traffic patterns over 19th-century street misalignments. The lack of a municipal [[freeway]] (either through or around the city) as well as the presence of two significant railways (each with attendant switching yards and few over/underpasses) are the primary causes of [[rush hour]] congestion, along with construction and heavy snow. Thus, traffic times can be significantly variable, although major traffic jams are rare.<ref name=\"master\">{{cite web| url=http://www.london.ca/city-hall/master-plans-reports/master-plans/Documents/Transportation%20Master%20Plan.pdf| title=Transportation Master Plan| date=May 2013| publisher=City of London| pages=2\u201323| accessdate=17 December 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221358/http://www.london.ca/city-hall/master-plans-reports/master-plans/Documents/Transportation%20Master%20Plan.pdf| archivedate=17 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Wellington Road between Commissioners Road E and Southdale Road E is London's busiest section of roadway, with more than 46,000 vehicles using the span on an average day<ref name=volume>{{cite web| title=City of London Traffic Volume Data| author=City of London| date=2013| url=http://www.london.ca/residents/Roads-Transportation/traffic-management/Pages/Traffic-Volumes.aspx| accessdate=26 October 2011| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221612/http://www.london.ca/residents/Roads-Transportation/traffic-management/Pages/Traffic-Volumes.aspx| archivedate=17 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref> City council rejected early plans for the construction of a freeway, and instead accepted the [[Veterans Memorial Parkway]] to serve the east end.<ref name=\"long-term\">{{cite web|title=Long-Term Transportation Corridor Protection Study |publisher=City of London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913040755/http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=%2FTransportation%2Fcorridorstudy.htm |archivedate=13 September 2013 |url=http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=/Transportation/corridorstudy.htm |accessdate=17 December 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some Londoners have expressed concern the absence of a local freeway may hinder London's economic and population growth, while others have voiced concern such a freeway would destroy environmentally sensitive areas and contribute to London's suburban sprawl.<ref name=\"master\" /> Road capacity improvements have been made to Veterans Memorial Parkway (formerly named Airport Road and [[Highway 100 (Ontario)|Highway 100]]) in the industrialized east end.<ref name=401images>{{cite web| archivedate=7 August 2007| title=King's Highway 401 \u2013 Images| last=Steeves| first=Scott| year=2004| url=http://www.onthighways.com/hwy_401_images/Hwy401_p4_images.htm| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807234534/http://onthighways.com/hwy_401_images/Hwy401_p4_images.htm| accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> However, the Parkway has received criticism for not being built as a proper highway; a recent city-run study suggested upgrading it by replacing the intersections with interchanges.<ref name=veterans07>{{cite web| title=Veterans Memorial Parkway| year=2007| publisher=City of London| url=http://www.london.ca/residents/Environment/EAs/Documents/VMP-PicBoard2.pdf| accessdate=17 December 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217224349/http://www.london.ca/residents/Environment/EAs/Documents/VMP-PicBoard2.pdf| archivedate=17 December 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Public transit ===\n{{main|Streetcars in London, Ontario|Shift (rapid transit)}}\n[[File:London Transit New Flyer.jpg|thumb|right|London Transit Commission bus]]\nIn the late 19th Century, and the early 20th Century, an extensive network of streetcar routes served London.<ref name=SkyriseCities2016-05-16/><ref name=Lfp2015-12-06/>\n\nLondon's [[Public transport|public transit]] system is run by the [[London Transit|London Transit Commission]], which has 44 bus routes throughout the city.<ref name=\"transit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ltconline.ca/Routes.htm|title=Routes and Schedules|publisher=London Transit Commission|accessdate=19 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918223851/http://www.ltconline.ca/Routes.htm|archivedate=18 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Although the city has lost ridership over the last few years, the commission is making concerted efforts to enhance services by implementing a five-year improvement plan. In 2015, an additional 17,000 hours of bus service was added throughout the city. In 2016, 11 new operators, 5 new buses, and another 17,000 hours of bus service were added to the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/2016/08/16/more-hours-new-names-for-routes-coming-next-month-as-overhaul-of-the-london-transit-commission-enters-next-phase|title=LTC rolling out big changes|last=nurun.com|website=The London Free Press|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019212621/http://www.lfpress.com/2016/08/16/more-hours-new-names-for-routes-coming-next-month-as-overhaul-of-the-london-transit-commission-enters-next-phase|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all|date=16 August 2016}}</ref>  Bus service is currently the only mode of public transit available to the public in London, with no available [[rapid transit]] networks like those used in other Canadian cities. However, city council approved a [[bus rapid transit]] (BRT) network, named [[Shift (rapid transit)|Shift]], in May 2016. The network will consist of two corridors serving each end of the city, and meeting at a central hub in the downtown. Construction is expected to begin in 2018, with the service fully operational by 2025.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.shiftlondon.ca/timeline|title=Timeline|newspaper=Shift|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019215403/http://www.shiftlondon.ca/timeline|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n[[File:Bike Lane Wortley.jpg|thumb|left|A separated bike lane in Wortley Village]]\n\n=== Cycling network ===\nLondon has 330&nbsp;km (205&nbsp;mi) of cycling paths throughout the city, 91&nbsp;km (59&nbsp;mi) of which have been added since 2005.<ref name=\"londonbikes.ca\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.londonbikes.ca/document/1-new-updated-london-bikes-executive-summary|title=#1: NEW- Updated London ON Bikes Executive Summary {{!}} City of London Cycling Master Plan Update|website=www.londonbikes.ca|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019212815/https://www.londonbikes.ca/document/1-new-updated-london-bikes-executive-summary|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2016, London unveiled its first bike corrals, which replace parking for one vehicle with fourteen bicycle parking spaces, and fix-it stations, which provide cyclists with simple tools and a bicycle pump, throughout the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london.ca/newsroom/Pages/bike-carrols.aspx|title=City Unveils London's First Ever Bike Corrals and New Fix-it Stations|website=www.london.ca|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019213751/https://www.london.ca/newsroom/Pages/bike-carrols.aspx|archivedate=19 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In September 2016, city council approved a new 15 year cycling master plan that will see the construction of an additional 470&nbsp;km (292&nbsp;mi) of cycling paths added to the existing network.<ref name=\"londonbikes.ca\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lfpress.com/2016/09/06/london-bike-path-plan-ready-for-action|title=Cycling plan ready for public test ride|last=nurun.com|website=The London Free Press|access-date=2016-10-19|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020040003/http://www.lfpress.com/2016/09/06/london-bike-path-plan-ready-for-action|archivedate=20 October 2016|df=dmy-all|date=6 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Intercity transport ===\n[[File:VIA Rail Train London Ontario.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Via Rail]] station in downtown London is Canada's fourth-busiest railway terminal.]]\nLondon is on the [[Canadian National Railway]] main line between Toronto and [[Chicago]] (with a secondary main line to [[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor]]) and the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] main line between Toronto and Detroit.<ref name=\"edc\">{{cite web| url=http://www.londonedc.com/forsiteselectors/infrastructure/transportation/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809231730/http://www.londonedc.com/forsiteselectors/infrastructure/transportation/| archivedate=9 August 2007| title=Transportation| year=2006| publisher=London Economic Development Corporation| accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> [[Via Rail]] operates regional passenger service through [[London, Ontario railway station|London station]] as part of the [[Quebec City\u2013Windsor Corridor]], with connections to the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.viarail.ca/en/stations/ontario/london/routes| title=Train routes to/from London| publisher=Via Rail| accessdate=28 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904104043/http://www.viarail.ca/en/stations/ontario/london/routes| archivedate=4 September 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> Via Rail's London terminal is the fourth-busiest passenger terminal in Canada.<ref name=\"edc\" />\n\nLondon is also a destination for inter-city [[bus]] travellers. London is the seventh-busiest [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound Canada]] terminal in terms of passengers,<ref name=\"greyhound\">{{cite web| url=http://www.greyhound.ca/HOME/en/About/FactsAndFigures.aspx| title=Facts & Figures| publisher=Greyhound Canada| accessdate=28 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719100726/http://www.greyhound.ca/HOME/en/About/FactsAndFigures.aspx| archivedate=19 July 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> and connecting services radiate from London throughout [[southwestern Ontario]] and through to the American cities of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] and [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].\n\n[[London International Airport]] ([[IATA airport code|YXU]]) is the 12th busiest passenger airport in Canada and the 11th busiest airport in Canada by take-offs and landings.<ref name=\"edc\" /> It is served by airlines including [[Air Canada Express]], and [[WestJet]], and provides direct flights to both domestic and international destinations, including [[Toronto]], [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Ottawa]], [[Winnipeg]], [[Calgary]], [[Canc\u00fan]], [[Vancouver]], [[Varadero]], [[Punta Cana]], [[Montego Bay]], [[Santa Clara, Cuba|Santa Clara]], and [[Holguin]].<ref name=airport>{{cite web| url=http://www.londonairport.on.ca/airlines.html| title=Airlines and Tour Operators| publisher=London International Airport| accessdate=19 February 2011| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304003935/http://www.londonairport.on.ca/airlines.html| archivedate=4 March 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Plans ===\n[[File:London International Airport arrivals outside.jpg|thumb|right|[[London International Airport]]]]\nThe city of London is considering [[bus rapid transit]] (BRT) and/or [[high-occupancy vehicle lane]]s (HOV) to help it achieve its long-term transportation plan. Additional cycleways are planned for integration in road-widening projects, where there is need and sufficient space along routes. An [[limited-access road|expressway]]/freeway network is possible along the eastern and western ends of the city, from [[Ontario Highway 401|Highway 401]] (and [[Ontario Highway 402|Highway 402]] for the western route) past Oxford Street, potentially with another highway, joining the two in the city's north end.<ref name=\"master\"/>\n\nThe City of London has assessed the entire length of the Veterans Memorial Parkway, identifying areas where interchanges can be constructed, grade separations can occur, and where [[cul-de-sac]]s can be placed. Upon completion, the Veterans Memorial Parkway would no longer be an expressway, but a freeway, for the majority of its length.<ref>{{cite web| title= Veterans Memorial Parkway Interchange Class Environmental Assessment Study and Concurrent Application to Amend the Official Plan and Zoning By-Law| author= City of London and Giffels| date= 13 December 2007| url= http://www.london.ca/residents/Environment/EAs/Documents/VMP-PicBoard2.pdf| accessdate= 17 December 2013| url-status= live| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131217224349/http://www.london.ca/residents/Environment/EAs/Documents/VMP-PicBoard2.pdf| archivedate= 17 December 2013| df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[File:UniversityCollegeUWO.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Middlesex Memorial Tower, University College, [[University of Western Ontario]]]]\n{{See also|List of schools in London, Ontario}}\n\nLondon public [[Primary education|elementary]] and [[Secondary education|secondary schools]] are governed by four [[Board of education|school boards]] \u2013 the [[Thames Valley District School Board]], the [[London District Catholic School Board]] and the French first-language school boards (the ''[[Conseil scolaire Viamonde]]'' and the ''[[Conseil scolaire catholique Providence]]'' or CSC).<ref name=\"london-edu\" /> The CSC has a satellite office in London.<ref>\"[http://www.cscprovidence.ca/fr/nous-joindre/3-bureau-satellite-de-london-middlesex Bureau satellite de London / Middlesex].\" ''Conseil scolaire catholique Providence''. Retrieved on 15 December 2014. \"Adresse: 920, rue Huron London Ontario N5Y 4K4 Canada\"</ref>\n\nThere are also more than twenty private schools in the city.<ref name=\"london-edu\">{{cite web|url=http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=/Education/default.htm |title=Education |year=2009 |publisher=City of London |accessdate=28 September 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806084408/http://london.ca/d.aspx?s=%2FEducation%2Fdefault.htm |archivedate=6 August 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLondon is home to [[London Central Secondary School]], the highest-ranking academic school in Ontario.<ref name=fraser>{{cite web |url=http://ontario.compareschoolrankings.org/secondary/SchoolsByRankLocationName.aspx |title=Compare academic rankings and ratings of Ontario schools |website=The Fraser Institute |accessdate=30 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108173113/http://ontario.compareschoolrankings.org/secondary/SchoolsByRankLocationName.aspx |archivedate=8 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe city is home to two [[Higher education|post-secondary]] institutions: the [[University of Western Ontario]] (UWO) and [[Fanshawe College]], a college of applied arts and technology.<ref name=\"london-edu\"/> UWO, founded in 1878, has about 3,500 full-time faculty and staff members and almost 30,000 [[undergraduate]] and [[Graduate School|graduate]] students.<ref name=\"about-uwo\">{{cite web| url=http://communications.uwo.ca/about/waywewere.htm| title=About Western| publisher=University of Western Ontario| accessdate=28 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209040802/http://communications.uwo.ca/about/waywewere.htm| archivedate=9 February 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> It placed tenth in the 2008 ''[[Maclean's]]'' magazine rankings of Canadian [[universities]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://communications.uwo.ca/com/western_news/stories/western_10th_in_maclean%27s_ranking_20081111443145/ |title=Western 10th in Maclean's ranking |last=Travis |first=Heather |date=11 November 2008 |work=Western News |publisher=University of Western Ontario |accessdate=28 September 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091222233904/http://communications.uwo.ca/com/western_news/stories/western_10th_in_maclean%27s_ranking_20081111443145/ |archivedate=22 December 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Richard Ivey School of Business]], part of UWO, was formed in 1922 and ranked among the best [[business school]]s in the country by the [[Financial Times]] in 2009.<ref name=\"mba\">{{cite web| url=http://rankings.ft.com/businessschoolrankings/global-mba-rankings| title=Global MBA Rankings 2009| year=2009| work=[[Financial Times]]| accessdate=24 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504135153/http://rankings.ft.com/businessschoolrankings/global-mba-rankings| archivedate=4 May 2011| df=dmy-all}}</ref> UWO has three affiliated colleges: [[Brescia University College]], founded in 1919 (Canada's only university-level women's college);<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brescia.uwo.ca/about/ |title=About |publisher=Brescia University College |accessdate=August 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827122345/http://brescia.uwo.ca/about/ |archive-date=27 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Huron University College]], founded in 1863 (also the founding college of UWO) and [[King's University College (University of Western Ontario)|King's University College]], founded in 1954.<ref name=HUChistorical>{{cite web |url=http://www.huronuc.on.ca/about_huron/more_about_huron/historical_information/ |title=Historical Information |publisher=Huron University College |accessdate=28 September 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618074047/http://www.huronuc.on.ca/about_huron/more_about_huron/historical_information/ |archivedate=18 June 2008}}</ref><ref name=kingsfacts>{{cite web| url=http://www.kings.uwo.ca/about/quick_facts/| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811074319/http://www.kings.uwo.ca/about/quick_facts/| archivedate=11 August 2010| title=Quick Facts| publisher=King's University College| accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> All three are [[liberal arts college]]s with religious affiliations: Huron with the [[Anglican Church of Canada]], King's and Brescia with the Roman Catholic Church.<ref name=\"ipb\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ipb.uwo.ca/facts.php| title=Western Facts| year=2008| publisher=University of Western Ontario| accessdate=24 September 2009| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612210617/http://www.ipb.uwo.ca/facts.php| archivedate=12 June 2009| df=dmy-all}}</ref> London is also home to [[Lester B. Pearson School for the Arts]] one of few of its kind.\n\nFanshawe College has an enrollment of approximately 15,000 students, including 3,500 apprentices and over 500 international students from more than 30 countries.<ref name=\"fanshawe-why\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fanshawec.ca/EN/counsellors/teachers/why.html|title=Why Fanshawe?|publisher=Fanshawe College|accessdate=28 September 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091011102418/http://www.fanshawec.ca/EN/counsellors/teachers/why.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=11 October 2009}}</ref> It also has almost 40,000 students in part-time [[continuing education]] courses.<ref name=\"fanshawe-why\" />  Fanshawe's [[Key performance indicators|Key Performance Indicators]] (KPI) have been over the provincial average for many years now, with increasing percentages year by year.<ref name=\"kpi\">{{cite web| url=http://www.fanshawec.ca/EN/kpi/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515041321/http://www.fanshawec.ca/EN/kpi/| archivedate=15 May 2008|title=Key Performance Indicators| publisher=Fanshawe College| accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ontario Institute of Audio Recording Technology]] (OIART), founded in 1983, offers recording studio experience for audio engineering students.<ref name=oiart>{{cite web| url=http://www.oiart.org/school/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722023053/http://www.oiart.org/school/| url-status=dead| archive-date=22 July 2011| title=Practical Studio Experience| publisher=OIART| accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Westervelt College]] is also in London. This private career college was founded in 1885 and offers several diploma programs.<ref name=westervelt>{{cite web| url=http://www.westervelt.ca/default.aspx| title=Westervelt College| publisher=Westervelt College| accessdate=28 August 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906131450/http://www.westervelt.ca/Default.aspx| archivedate=6 September 2013| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n* [[CFB London]]\n* [[List of people from London, Ontario]]\n* [[List of royal visits to London, Ontario]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in London, Ontario]]\n* [[Asteroid]] [[12310 Londontario]], named for the city.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=SkyriseCities2016-05-16>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://skyrisecities.com/news/2016/05/once-upon-tram-london-street-railway-companys-60-year-run-ontario\n |title       = Once Upon a Tram: The London Street Railway Company's 60-year Run in Ontario\n |author      = Adrian Gamble\n |date        = 2016-05-16\n |accessdate  = 2017-03-16\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170317054816/http://skyrisecities.com/news/2016/05/once-upon-tram-london-street-railway-companys-60-year-run-ontario\n |archivedate = 17 March 2017\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n\n<ref name=Lfp2015-12-06>\n{{cite news\n |url         = https://lfpress.com/2015/12/06/its-back-to-the-transit-future\n |title       = It's back to the transit future\n |author      = Patrick Maloney\n |newspaper   = The London Free Press\n |date        = 2015-12-06\n |accessdate  = 2017-03-16\n |quote       = But O\u2019Neil, a local-history buff, has unearthed a document that suggests the proposed rail lines for London\u2019s rapid-transit proposal are perfectly placed. He found a map outlining London\u2019s streetcar lines in 1914, and notes the two lines earmarked today for light rail are where the old trolleys ran a century ago.\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20170316205548/http://www.lfpress.com/2015/12/06/its-back-to-the-transit-future\n |archivedate = 16 March 2017\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book| last1=Armstrong| first1=Frederick H| last2=Lutman| first2=John| title=The Forest City: An Illustrated History of London, Canada| publisher=Windsor Publications| year=1986| isbn=978-0897811804| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/forestcityillust0000arms}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|London, Ontario}}\n{{wikivoyage|London (Ontario)|London, Ontario}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{London, Ontario}}\n{{Geographic location  <!-- This geo box is for DIRECTLY ADJACENT municipalities as standardized for all other municipalities -->|\nNorth=[[Middlesex Centre, Ontario|Middlesex Centre]]|\nWest=[[Middlesex Centre, Ontario|Middlesex Centre]]|\nCenter=London|\nEast=[[Thames Centre, Ontario|Thames Centre]]|\nSouth=[[Southwold, Ontario|Southwold]], [[Central Elgin]]|\n}}\n{{Navboxes|list =\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Census metropolitan areas by size}}}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:London, Ontario| ]]\n[[Category:Single-tier municipalities in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Southwestern Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = London\n| official_name                   = City of London\n| settlement_type                 = City ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Single-tier municipalities|single-tier]])\n| image_skyline                   = {{multiple image\n| border                 = infobox\n| total_width            = 290\n| image_style            = border:1;\n| perrow                 = 1/2/1/2\n| image1                 = London Ontario Skyline 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| image2                 = Thames River Springbank Park.jpg\n| image3                 = University College Building University of Western Ontario 1.jpg\n}}\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption            